<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caravaggio Work at National Gallery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To Christians it's one of the most dramatic  
moments of their faith, the kiss of Judas and the arrest of Jesus 
in the Garden of Gethsemane. To art lovers, it's the long ``lost'' 
depiction of that moment by one of the greatest of Italian artists, 
Michelangelo Merisi -- better known as Caravaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	For centuries labeled the work of a minor Dutch painter, ``The  
Taking of Christ,'' was identified in 1990 by Sergio Benedetti, a 
senior restorer at the National Gallery of Ireland. He found it in 
the dining room of a house of Jesuit priests in Dublin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're almost certain that the figure in the upper right,  
holding a lantern, is a self-portrait of Caravaggio,'' Benedetti 
told reporters at the painting's first appearance in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Gallery of Art has no Caravaggio -- only about 35 of  
his paintings survive. Its exhibit opening Sunday surrounds this 
one with eight Italian, French and Spanish paintings that relate to 
Caravaggio's distinctive style. 
</P>
<P>
	Caravaggio brings the viewer into the picture by crowding his  
realistic, vividly colored figures close together and painting 
light and dark areas in dramatic contrast. Illumination seems to 
come from above, as if from heaven. But the lantern, held by the 
figure who is apparently Caravaggio, serves mostly to light up his 
own partly hidden face. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Taking of Christ'' was painted in 1602 for the wealthy  
Mattei family of Rome. Caravaggio had a bad reputation there and 
fled after killing a man in a brawl about a tennis match. He died 
at 39. 
</P>
<P>
	The Matteis fell on hard times and 200 years later they sold  
some of their paintings to William Hamilton Nesbit, a rich Scotsman 
who often visited Italy. He labeled it ``The Betrayal of Christ,'' 
by Gerard van Honthorst, a follower of Caravaggio who had some 
reputation of his own. It was in the family for more than a 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	After that family died out, an auction house in Edinburgh,  
Scotland, tried to sell six of its pictures -- including the 
Caravaggio -- but withdrew them when the lot failed to reach the 
paintings' asking price of about $250. 
</P>
<P>
	The Caravaggio has been valued recently at more than $30  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Noel Barber, superior of the Jesuit residence that owns  
the painting, told reporters it was acquired by the widow of a 
British police inspector who gave it to the Jesuits because one of 
them helped her in her grief after her husband was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	It hung in the community's house for the next 30 years, until  
Barber got the National Gallery of Ireland to restore it as a work 
of van Honthorst. Benedetti recognized it as a Caravaggio almost at 
once, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The painting has been on exhibit at the Irish gallery, and until  
May 24 at the McMullen Museum of Art at Boston University. ``The 
Taking of Christ'' will be at the National Gallery until July 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
