<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sara Boutelle    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) -- Sara Boutelle, an architectural  
historian who rediscovered the work of the woman who designed 
William Randolph Hearst's California castle, died Wednesday. She 
was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Ms. Boutelle published ``Julia Morgan, Architect'' in  
1988, little was known about Morgan beyond her work on Hearst's 
spectacular castle, San Simeon. 
</P>
<P>
	Her book revealed that Morgan designed nearly 800 buildings, a  
legacy rivaling that of Frank Lloyd Wright. Her accomplishment also 
came at a time when women were rarely able to enter the profession. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Boutelle discovered that Morgan had worked alone and  
destroyed most of her blueprints shortly before her death in 1957. 
She reconstructed Morgan's designs from the scattered records of 
her former clients. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, Ms. Boutelle was made an honorary member of the  
American Institute of Architects, the highest award the 
organization gives to someone who is not an architect. 

</P>
<P>
 *Frank Gunther    	
</P>
<P>
	VENICE, Fla. (AP) -- Frank Gunther, who devised some of the first  
radio communications devices, died Monday. He was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Gunther helped create shortwave, two-way and FM systems, often  
working with the military and police and fire departments. In 1932 
he built what is believed to be the first two-way mobile police 
radio system for the Bayonne, N.J., police department. 
</P>
<P>
	Gunther also installed one of the first one-way radios used on  
an aircraft. In 1931, he took part in the first public broadcast 
from an aircraft. A year later he installed the first two-way radio 
system on an airplane. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined Radio Engineering Laboratories in 1925. It was there  
that he constructed and operated an experimental station that was 
one of the first shortwave broadcasting systems. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1935, Gunther and Edwin Armstrong gave the first public  
demonstration of frequency modulation, or FM transmission. The 
signal was much superior in clarity to AM or shortwave. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Charles F. McErlean Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) -- Charles F. McErlean Sr., former president  
of UAL Inc., the parent company of United Airlines, died May 21. He 
was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	With a law degree and a background with the National Labor  
Relations Board, McErlean was hired in 1945 by W.A. Patterson, 
founder of United Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	He started the company's legal department and held several jobs  
over the next few decades, including vice president, senior vice 
president and was a member of the company's board of directors. He 
rose to United vice chairman and UAL president. 
</P>
<P>
	McErlean was considered a strong administrator who played an  
active role in labor negotiations over the years. 

</P>
<P>
 *Richard Ray    	
</P>
<P>
	MACON, Ga. (AP) -- Richard Ray, a former representative known for  
his advocacy for veterans and the military bases in his west 
Georgia district, died Saturday from complications related to 
emergency heart valve replacement surgery last week. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray was elected to Congress in 1982 after serving 10 years as an  
aide to former Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn. He was defeated in 1992 and 
started a consulting firm in Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Congress, Ray often found himself at odds with fellow  
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1983, Ray irritated the Democratic House leadership when he  
was one of only six Democrats to vote against the party's budget 
proposal. He also opposed a resolution calling for a nuclear freeze 
and voted against the Equal Rights Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray angered many blacks when he opposed designating Martin  
Luther King Jr.'s birthday as a federal holiday, saying the country 
couldn't afford it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
