<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbus 2, Los Angeles 1 (SO) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Jeff Cunningham scored in the 88th minute  
to tie the game and scored the winning goal in the shootout round 
as the Columbus Crew beat the Los Angeles Galaxy 2-1 in a Major 
League Soccer game tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Crew goalkeeper Mark Dougherty stopped consecutive shots by Cobi  
Jones, Welton and Mauricio Cienfuegoes in the shootout round. With 
the win, Dougherty tied the MLS all-time record of 42 wins set by 
Dallas' Mark Dodd. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Thompson and Stern John also scored for the Crew in the  
shootout round against Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman. Thompson 
flicked a shot over the head of the onrushing Hartman, and 
Cunningham and John dribbled around the league's best goalkeeper to 
score. 
</P>
<P>
	After stopping several point-blank shots by John, Hartman was on  
his way to his sixth shutout of the year. But Cunningham took a 
pass from Matt Kmosko inside the box, dribbled around a defender 
and fired a hard shot past Hartman for his fourth goal of the year. 
The goal was only the seventh Hartman has allowed all season. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones put Los Angeles up 1-0 in the 57th minute on a goal from  
18 yards out. That was after Crew defender Mike Clark headed his 
first shot back to him. Jones collected the ball and sent the shot 
past Dougherty for his second goal of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal was the first the Crew had allowed in a team-record of  
290 minutes of regulation play. 
</P>
<P>
	The Galaxy outshot the Crew 15-to-9 but the Crew led 4-to-2 in  
shots on goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the shootout win, Columbus (7-3) falls to second place  
in the Eastern Conference because Washington D.C. won Saturday in 
regulation. The Galaxy (5-6) remain in fourth place in the Western 
Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
