<HEADLINE> Man Convicted of Killing Prosecutor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A reputed gang leader was convicted Saturday in  
the execution-style slaying of a gang prosecutor who had dogged him 
for over a year. 
</P>
<P>
	After nearly three days of deliberations, jurors found  
24-year-old Jeffrey Bly guilty of the 1995 shooting of Assistant 
Attorney General Paul McLaughlin outside a commuter rail station in 
the city's West Roxbury section. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Bly executed McLaughlin, 42, because he feared  
going to jail on carjacking charges. He was subsequently convicted 
on those charges and is currently serving a 10- to 15-year sentence 
in state prison. 
</P>
<P>
	McLaughlin's 78-year-old father, former Lt. Gov. Edward F.  
McLaughlin Jr., told the court that though Bly's actions were 
``vicious and cowardly,'' the family has chosen to focus instead on 
the life and accomplishments of his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though Jeffrey Bly pulled the trigger to extinguish  
(Paul's) life, he didn't -- nor could he ever -- extinguish his 
memory,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bly was sentenced to life imprisonment with no chance of parole  
for McLaughlin's death, the automatic penalty for a first-degree 
murder conviction in Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	Using eyewitnesses, DNA evidence, and the word of Bly's  
acquaintances, prosecutors spun a web that tied Bly to the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers assailed the credibility of witnesses, denounced  
physical evidence as junk science, and said Bly was nowhere near 
McLaughlin at the time of the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	In the eight months prior to his death Sept. 25, 1995,  
McLaughlin had unsuccessfully tried Bly twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Bly, leader of the Theodore Street Posse in  
Boston's Mattapan neighborhood, had a vendetta against the lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecution witnesses testified that Bly bragged of taking out  
the prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to worry about the DA no more,'' Janet Brown said  
Bly told her. ``I shot him two or three times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Houston testified that Bly ordered him to stalk  
McLaughlin three days before the shooting and make note of the 
prosecutor's routine. He said he wrote down McLaughlin's license 
plate number for Bly. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA evidence recovered from bloodstained gloves, a sweatshirt  
and hat dumped along railroad tracks, tied Bly to the crime, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	A fragment of McLaughlin's eyeglasses was found on the glove,  
and prosecutors said authorities recovered Bly's genetic material 
from the clothing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
