<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Male Guard Wins Sex Harassment Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT HOLLY, N.J. (AP) -- A male prison guard who sued after a  
female co-worker repeatedly tried to seduce him has won a $3.75 
million sexual harassment award. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury found Friday that New Jersey corrections officials did  
nothing to stop the harassment of Robert Lockley Jr., even after he 
complained to supervisors at the Mid-State Correctional Facility at 
Fort Dix. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also determined that Lockley's co-workers and  
supervisors retaliated against him after he reported the 
harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	He was awarded $3 million in punitive damages and $750,000 in  
compensatory damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big win,'' said Lockley, 39, of Willingboro.  
</P>
<P>
	Lockley sued in 1994 alleging Ronda Turner, 37, began harassing  
him in 1990. He said she called him up to invite him to her home, 
but he declined, saying he was married and not interested. Turner 
then began following him around the prison grounds, repeatedly 
asking him to go out with her or have sex, according to the 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the common and usual situation,'' said Marcia  
Greenberger, co-president of the National Women's Law Center, which 
won a case before the Supreme Court last week involving sexual 
harassment in public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Rita Malley, spokeswoman for the state attorney general, said  
the state plans to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockley still works at Mid-State with Turner and other  
co-workers accused of retaliating. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's refused to go to lunch because he hasn't wanted to deal  
with them,'' said his attorney, Linda Wong. ``He goes to his tower 
and eats his lunch there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
