<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lowell Joins Marlins After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Testicular cancer gave Florida Marlins rookie third  
baseman Mike Lowell a scare, a new perspective and an extra reason 
to savor his National League debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 24 hours after being recalled from Triple-A, Lowell  
was in the lineup for Saturday night's game against the Cincinnati 
Reds. He went 0-for-4 with two strikeouts and an error in the 
Marlins' 8-1 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell's season was sidetracked by surgery Feb. 21 to remove a  
small testicular mass found during a routine physical examination. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a life perspective, things have been put in their place  
because of this,'' Lowell said before the game. ``From a baseball 
standpoint, I don't think my attitude has changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not one to be complacent. I'm going to be aggressive on  
the field. This is kind of like survival of the fittest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell, who grew up in Miami, hit 56 homers in 1997-98 in the  
New York Yankees' farm system, then was traded Feb. 1 to Florida 
for three pitching prospects. He hopes to bolster an offense that 
ranks next-to-last in the major leagues in runs, but he admits that 
surgery has temporarily robbed him of the power he had last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can play every day. From that standpoint, I'm 100 percent,''  
said Lowell, 25. ``Strength-wise, I don't know if I'm going to be 
100 percent the whole year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Triple-A Calgary, Lowell hit .313 with two homers and nine  
RBIs in 83 at-bats. His rehabilitation was complicated by soreness 
in his throwing shoulder that has since subsided. 
</P>
<P>
	Following surgery, Lowell underwent a short course of low-dose  
radiation, and he said his prognosis is excellent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Health-wise everything has been best-case scenario,'' he said.  
``I can't complain. Things could have been worse. I'm just happy to 
be on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins' third baseman for most of the season, Kevin Orie,  
went on the disabled list Friday with a pulled groin. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell emerged as a top prospect last year, when he hit .304 at  
Triple-A Columbus with 26 homers and 99 RBIs. He believes he's 
ready for the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what I've wanted to do, so you can't shy away from  
it,'' he said. ``You have to have confidence in yourself.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
