<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mississippi Flag Suit Fuels Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court's decision to  
reinstate a lawsuit against Mississippi's use of the Confederate 
battle flag in the state banner has refueled fiery rhetoric over 
the divisive symbol. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucked in a corner of Mississippi's state banner, the stars and  
bars is an anchor for some proud Southerners, but a painful 
reminder of a segregationist history for others. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court on Thursday reinstated a lawsuit filed by the  
NAACP and dozens of black Mississippians that challenges the 
continued use of the Confederate symbol. 
</P>
<P>
	``Outside the state they think we're still fighting the Civil  
War,'' Bennie Turner, a black leader in the state Senate, said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jim Giles, the outspoken head of a group that promotes  
Southern heritage and champions the Confederate flag, says the flag 
has nothing to do with racism. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a visceral, emotional feeling of pride,'' said Giles,  
head of the Southern Initiative. ``We all descend from a group of 
people who fought under that flag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He believes flag opponents are agitators and has a two-word  
message for them: ``get out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There ain't no fences around Mississippi, they can go  
somewhere else,'' said Giles, an independent candidate for 
governor. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People  
filed the original suit six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they have an uphill battle,'' said Mike Barefield,  
attorney for United Sons of Confederate Veterans. ``This has been 
decided in a number of courts already and every time it's 
dismissed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a different case last fall, the state Supreme Court refused  
to ban use of a Confederate flag on the Gulf Coast as part of a 
historical flag display. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the ruling, Justice Fred Banks said the flag ``has been  
used throughout history, not only to commemorate the sacrifices 
made in support of the Confederacy, but -- most importantly -- as a 
symbol of white supremacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The banner has a condensed version of the Confederate flag in  
the upper left hand corner, with red, white and blue stripes 
covering the remainder of the flag. Its design was recommended by a 
special committee to the Legislature in 1894. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very offensive. It conjures up all the emotions that the  
swastika conjures up for Jewish people,'' said Ed Blackmon, a state 
representative and one of the plaintiffs in the suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 05:01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Radio Host Sues Former Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Syndicated radio talk show host Art Bell is  
suing two former guests, accusing them of making slanderous 
statements on the air and causing his listenership to decline. 
</P>
<P>
	The $60 million lawsuit, filed Thursday in Los Angeles Superior  
Court, claims the men knowingly made false statements, such as Bell 
had been jailed for trafficking in pornography. Bell said he has 
never been arrested for any crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Stephens, of St. Ignatius, Mont., appeared on a radio  
show hosted by David John Oates, of Colorado, on April 3 and the 
two conspired to damage Bell's reputation, according to the 
lawsuit. A recording of the show is also available on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims Bell has had to reduce his time on the air  
``to respond to false and defamatory statements and deal with the 
emotional distress those statements have caused him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Associated Press was unable to locate Oates and Stephens for  
comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell hosts ``Coast to Coast AM with Art Bell,'' the nation's  
most listened-to overnight show. In October, Bell abruptly signed 
off citing a ``threatening terrible event'' involving his family, 
only to return just as suddenly about two weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's lawyer in Los Angeles, Gerard Fox, said his client was  
seeking to protect his reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	``He also does not believe that the idea of accountability and  
free speech are mutually exclusive,'' Fox said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
