<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Behrens Wins Massachusetts Handicap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Behrens made a powerful move coming off the final  
turn and beat Running Stag by a half length to win the $600,000 
Grade II Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet, winner of the 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness  
Stakes, was second at the half-mile pole but gave way in the 
stretch and finished third as the 4-5 favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder of the field in the 60th running of the 1 1/8-mile  
race in their order of finish were Brushing Up, Galloping Gael, and 
Personal Moon. 
</P>
<P>
	By winning $400,000 in a time of 1:49.14, Behrens took a 28-20  
lead over both Free House and Puerto Madero in the NTRA Champions 
Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Behrens, the second favorite, paid $3.80, $3.20 and $2.20.  
Running Stag paid $5.40 and $2.20, while Real Quiet returned $2.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Running Stag took the lead at the start and stayed in front to  
mid-stretch where he drifted and was caught by Behrens. 
</P>
<P>
	``We definitely didn't expect Running Stag to go to the lead,''  
Behrens trainer H. James Bond said. ``We thought Real Quiet was the 
horse to beat and we kept an eye on him the whole time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Mitchell, trainer of Running Stag, conceded that he  
employed a different stategy for the MassCap. 
</P>
<P>
	``We changed tactics in this race and it worked beautifully,''  
Mitchell said. ``I think we might have a horse that likes to run on 
the front end now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet was the first Kentucky Derby winner to run in the  
MassCap since Riva Ridge won the race in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	``Running Stag had acted like he might have wanted the lead.  
There was really no pace in the race,'' Real Quiet jockey Gary 
Stevens said. ``We picked up the other two (Running Stag and 
Behrens) about four and a half furlongs out. As soon as I started 
putting him down, he started to tire.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
