<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Quest for Kosovo Peace Eludes Envoys  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- European leaders struggled to revive  
their quest for a diplomatic way out of the Kosovo crisis today, 
but common ground remained elusive as NATO renewed its pledge to 
pound away at Yugoslavia until the alliance's terms for peace are 
met. NATO said it had hit hard at Serb forces in Kosovo during the 
previous 24 hours, attacking tanks and artillery pieces, as well as 
airfields and other targets across Yugoslavia. Local media reported 
that six people were killed today. Serbian media reported more 
civilian casualties, including two deaths in the village of 
Cumurjila outside Nis in central Serbia. 

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon Sends More Jets to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon today ordered 68 U.S. planes to  
join about 1,000 allied aircraft fighting in Kosovo, and Secretary 
of State Madeleine Albright blamed President Slobodan Milosevic of 
Yugoslavia for prolonging the 10-week air war. ``Milosevic's 
brutality made NATO's response necessary,'' Albright told graduates 
of Georgetown University's School of Foreign Service. She said NATO 
bombs inadvertently have killed civilians, despite ``great pains'' 
to avoid deadly errors. The 48 Air Force fighter jets and 20 
tankers will head for Europe next week, bringing to 769 the number 
of U.S. planes involved in the airstrikes that began March 24. 

</P>
<P>
	Vitter Wins Louisiana Race  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Former state Rep. David Vitter was elected  
today as Bob Livingston's successor in Congress, winning a close 
election over former Gov. Dave Treen. With 99 percent of the 
precincts reporting, Vitter got 60,699 votes, or 51 percent, to 
Treen's 58,825 votes, or 49 percent. The two solidly conservative 
Republican lawyers, both veteran politicians, struggled to point 
out their differences after they were the top finishers in a field 
of nine in a May 1 primary. Vitter, 38, hoped to use youth to his 
advantage, saying the 70-year-old Treen's influence would be 
diminished because of his age. 

</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Ready for Spacewalk  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- After Discovery's astronauts docked  
flawlessly with the new international space station today, they 
geared up for their next adventure: a late-night stroll to spruce 
up the station's outside. Among their duties during the six-hour 
outing: attaching a pair of 5-foot cranes to the exterior of the 
station, hanging out bags of tools for future spacewalkers, 
installing a glare-reducing shroud over a docking target, and 
covering an exposed pin. The spacewalk, by Tamara Jernigan and Dr. 
Daniel Barry, was expected to last into the wee hours tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Prosecutors Want Tripp Tapes  
</P>
<P>
	ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- Maryland prosecutors have asked the  
federal judge overseeing a grand jury investigation of President 
Clinton for access to Linda Tripp's secret tape recordings of 
Monica Lewinsky, a newspaper reported. State prosecutors filed the 
request with U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, 
unidentified sources told The (Baltimore) Sun today. A Maryland 
grand jury is considering whether Mrs. Tripp broke Maryland law by 
recording conversations with Ms. Lewinsky. If tried and convicted, 
she could get five years in prison and a $10,000 fine. 

</P>
