<DOCNO> APW19990529.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 16:31:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians' Wright Defends His Pitching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Gene Budig didn't need a 95 mph fastball to  
back Jaret Wright off the plate and get inside the pitcher's head. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright said his poor start last night against the Red Sox may  
have been partially caused by Budig's request that Wright appear in 
the AL president's office next week to discuss the pitcher's 
behavior on the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who earlier this season was suspended for five games for  
hitting Boston outfielder Darren Lewis, was ordered in by Budig 
after being fined this week for his role in a brawl with the 
Detroit Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went out there trying not to let it, trying not to think  
about it, but I think it did a little bit,'' Wright said Saturday. 
``I think I was out there and I let it get into my head a little 
bit. ... Still, there's no excuse for bad pitching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After he was hammered for eight runs and nine hit in a  
season-low 3 2-3 innings, Wright didn't wait around to talk with 
reporters after Boston's 12-5 victory Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	So following batting practice Saturday, Wright met the media in  
the Cleveland dugout to discuss his upcoming meeting with Budig and 
to dispute charges that he is a headhunter. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright said he was taken off guard by Budig's public  
announcement that he would speak with the 23-year-old pitcher about 
his ``deportment on the mound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically when I heard that, I was surprised like everybody  
else,'' he said. ``I didn't necessarily agree with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who dropped to 4-3 with a 6.95 ERA following Friday's  
disaster, said he wouldn't speculate on what Budig might want to 
talk about. But he did make it clear he thinks charges that he's 
throwing at hitters are out of line. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I threw the ball everywhere that I wanted to then I would  
get a lot more guys out,'' he said. ``I've never let a ball go out 
of my hand with the intention of hitting anyone in the head. 
</P>
<P>
	``When that happens that's not part of the game, it never has  
been. I was never taught that. For anyone to see that about me, 
that I'm a headhunter or something like that, that's not what I'm 
about. I'm out there to get guys out, to pitch in off the plate 
which I think is part of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never let a ball go with the intention of hitting someone  
in the head. No way. ... I've never tried to hit anyone in the 
head. I've never done anything like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright said he's shocked at all the attention his situation has  
been receiving. He acknowledged that pointing at his head after he 
hit Lewis last month was wrong, and admits he probably needs to get 
the ball down if he's going to challenge hitters inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think their (league) biggest problem is that the ball has  
been just a little high,'' he said. ``When I want to brush someone 
back or pitch in off the plate, it's been a little high and I 
understand that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright said he was unconcerned about where the accusations of  
headhunting started and his main goal now was to put the past 
behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that's wasted energy,'' he said. ``It wouldn't serve  
any purpose for me to find out where it started. I need to deal 
with what's happening right now and try to pitch a little better. 
That's about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indians catcher Sandy Alomar, currently sidelined following knee  
surgery, thinks Wright is being singled out by Budig because he's 
young and not an established veteran. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's very unfair to take a young guy and call him into  
the office,'' said Alomar. ``Jaret pitches inside and yesterday 
they took that part of his game away. That's not fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar said he can tell during a game when Wright's control is  
off, and when it is, Alomar says he stays in the middle of the 
plate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't move because I don't want to see anyone get hit,'' he  
said. ``If you're going to look at Jaret, you had better look at a 
lot of other guys in this league. Because Jaret sure isn't the only 
one who likes to pitch inside. You can't treat a young guy 
differently than a veteran. That's not right.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
