<DOCNO> APW19990529.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 12:01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman: Increase Military Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite large-scale troop deployments abroad,  
the U.S. military has shrunk 40 percent in a decade to a level 
incapable of adequately carrying out its missions, GOP Gov. 
Christie Whitman of New Jersey said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman, speaking in the party's weekly radio address, marked  
the Memorial Day commemoration with appeals for money to increase 
military readiness and to help veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very concerned that the budget the president has proposed  
abandons our obligation to veterans,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She complained that Department of Veterans Affairs hospitals in  
New Jersey lack the money to operate at full strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot and must not fail to care for those who suffer the  
scars of service,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the active duty forces, Whitman said: ``Our military has  
shrunk by 40 percent this decade, even as our president has been 
deploying troops at a record clip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said Navy ships have decreased from 546 to 333, fighter  
wings from 24 to 13, Army divisions from 18 to 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The forces are plagued by a shortage of air-launched cruise  
missiles, a $3.5 billion shortfall in ammunition, so few aircraft 
that planes had to be been diverted from no-fly operations in Iraq 
to airstrikes against Yugoslavia, Whitman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Downsizing the bureaucracy is one thing,'' she said.  
``Downsizing our defense is a risk our nation cannot afford.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a similar theme, conservative activist Gary Bauer, in Iowa  
campaigning for the 2000 presidential caucuses next February, said 
military budget problems have harmed the Balkan bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	He urged increased defense spending of $50 billion or more over  
the next six years. The Joint Chiefs of Staff have said they need 
an additional $60 billion to achieve full combat readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't afford to have our own military leaders telling us  
we're that far short,'' Bauer said at a news conference in Des 
Moines. ``I'm certainly gong to try to make it a major issue of the 
campaign.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
