<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Store Agrees to $8M in Refunds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federated Department Stores must make refunds  
totaling $8 million or more to customers illegally pursued for debt 
collection after they declared bankruptcy, the Federal Trade 
Commission said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission settlement ensures the Federated, which operates  
Bloomingdale's, Burdines, Macy's East, Macy's West and other 
retailers, fully reimburses consumers under a deal negotiated with 
numerous state attorneys general. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC alleged that Federated induced consumers into agreements  
to reaffirm their credit-account debts in order to keep purchased 
merchandise. The company told consumers it would file the 
reaffirmation agreements with bankruptcy courts, and the bankrupt 
customers would be legally obligated to pay. 
</P>
<P>
	In many cases, the FTC charged, the company never filed  
agreements or courts did not approve them. Such reaffirmation 
agreements are not illegal but by law must be filed with bankruptcy 
courts. If not filed or approved by the court, the agreements are 
unenforceable. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20,000 bankrupt debtors may have paid the company, even  
though the agreements were not binding. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Friday's settlement, Federated is prohibited from falsely  
claiming that any reaffirmation agreement is binding or has been 
filed with a bankruptcy court. The company also would be barred 
from collecting debts discharged by the bankruptcy courts. 
</P>
<P>
	Federated recently settled a multiple state action by agreeing  
to provide redress to customers who had paid debts they did not 
legally owe. Friday's settlement preserves the FTC's right to act 
against the company in federal court if the commission believes 
payments have not been made or if the redress amounts to less than 
$8.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	A settlement does not constitute an admission of wrongdoing.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 08:01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Making Claim in the Racing Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	You've heard it before: If Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner  
Charismatic takes the $1 million Belmont Stakes on June 5, he will 
become the first claiming horse to win a Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	But what exactly is a claiming horse, or, more popularly, a  
``claimer?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A claiming race means that any horse entered can be bought on  
the spot for a predetermined price. 
</P>
<P>
	When Charismatic ran for a ``tag'' on Feb. 11, a trainer on the  
grounds of Santa Anita could have filled out a form, dropped it in 
the claiming box 15 minutes before the race, and walked away with 
the future Kentucky Derby winner for the claiming price of $62,500. 
</P>
<P>
	By entering Charismatic in such a claiming race, trainer D.  
Wayne Lukas took the risk of losing him -- and fortunately for 
owners Bob and Beverly Lewis, that didn't happen. At the time, 
Lukas said he was ``scared to death'' someone would put in a claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Horses generally don't run in claiming races unless there is  
nowhere else for them to run. In other words, they're usually not 
fast enough to run in stakes races, nor do they have the ability to 
compete in allowance races against well-bred horses on their way to 
bigger and better things. 
</P>
<P>
	``Claiming races give horses the opportunity to run against  
lesser horses and also give owners the chance to make money,'' said 
Mike Lakow, racing secretary for the New York Racing Association. 
``If you have a real nice horse, you're taking a shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Charismatic's case, the Lewises were ready to give up on him  
after he won just two of nine starts. It was not the return they 
expected after shelling out $200,000 to purchase him as a weanling. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis put him in the February claiming race because ``quite  
frankly, I'd given up on the horse. I wanted to salvage as much of 
that original $200,000 investment as I could.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Claiming races comprise about 30-40 percent of the races run at  
the bigger meets and bigger racetracks in New York, California and 
Kentucky. At the smaller tracks, and during the winter, up to 80 
percent of races run are claiming races, with the purse and the 
claiming price just about equal. 
</P>
<P>
	Horses can run for as little as $1,500 or as much as $100,000.  
The races are usually competitive, as it makes no sense to run a 
horse worth $70,000 in a $35,000 race (you'd lose him), nor does it 
make sense to run a $35,000 horse in a $70,000 race (you'd have no 
chance to win). 
</P>
<P>
	And, its a cash-and-carry deal -- the person doing the claiming  
takes the horse ``as is'' as soon as the race is over, no matter 
what happens in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	It has happened that people have wound up claiming dead horses,  
and then, to add to the ignominy, the new owner is responsible for 
burial fees. The former owner gets to keep the purse money, if any. 
</P>
<P>
	Some trainers, such as Gasper Moschera and Mike Hushion in New  
York, specialize in the claiming game, continually taking horses 
and improving them before losing them again, but at a higher price. 
Hushion claimed Reappeal for $14,000 in December 1991, won 10 races 
and more than $175,000 with him, and lost him a year later for 
$25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainers such as Lukas, Shug McGaughey, Bill Mott or Bob  
Baffert, whose barns are filled with blue-blooded thoroughbreds, 
only occasionally send a horse into a claiming race, and usually it 
is a higher-priced race -- $50,000 and up. 
</P>
<P>
	Although claimers are considered lesser-caliber horses, stars  
have emerged from their ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1943, trainer Max Hirsch claimed a horse named Stymie for  
$1,500 and went on to win almost a $1 million with him. Kelly Kip, 
a multiple track record holder, started his career for Hall of Fame 
trainer Allen Jerkens in a maiden claiming race, in which he 
promptly broke the track record at Belmont for 5 1/2 furlongs. 
Moschera claimed a horse named Videogenic for $100,000 in 1985 in 
New York and went on to win 11 stakes races with her, including the 
Grade I Santa Ana and Ladies Handicaps. 
</P>
<P>
	And then, there's Charismatic.  
</P>
<P>
	``Isn't that incredible?'' Lewis said after the Kentucky Derby.  
``You can have a claimer today and all of a sudden have a champion 
tomorrow.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
