<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Strikes Serb Forces in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- European leaders struggled to revive  
their quest for a diplomatic way out of the Kosovo crisis today, 
but common ground remained elusive as NATO renewed its pledge to 
strike Yugoslavia until the alliance's terms for peace are met. The 
German and French prime ministers called for a new meeting of the 
leading industrial states and Russia to assess the results of talks 
between Moscow's Balkans envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana 
said during a visit to the Istrana base in northern Italy that he 
backs the French-German proposal, the Italian news agency AGI 
reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Group Says World Hotter, Stormier  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The world is getting hotter and Mother Nature  
madder, sperm counts are sinking in the United States and Europe, 
and the use of wind power is soaring, a millennium-ending snapshot 
of global trends finds. Worldwatch Institute's annual eclectic 
compilation of facts and figures, ``Vital Signs 1999,'' offers a 
little something for everyone making predictions about where the 
planet and its inhabitants are headed in the next century. An 
assessment by Worldwatch president Lester Brown in the report 
released today is that the latest data underscore big problems, 
with the average global temperature, weather-related damage and 
people displaced by storms all going ``off the charts.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dead Man Blamed in Wash. Rampage  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Authorities today were still trying to understand  
what sent a man on a killing spree, but first they had to tally the 
dead and wounded: his mother and nephew stabbed to death, a woman 
fatally beaten, another woman critically injured, a motorcyclist 
run over and a sheriff's deputy shot. Believed to be responsible 
for it all was 22-year-old Lonnie Davis, who was shot dead by a 
police sniper after a standoff with police in a northern suburb of 
Seattle. 

</P>
<P>
	1 Dead in Austrian Tunnel Fire  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- A truck loaded with paint crashed into  
the back of a car deep inside a tunnel in western Austria early 
today, setting off a chain reaction of explosions and a massive 
blaze that killed at least one person and injured dozens, officials 
said. Firefighters, who were initially unable to get at the fire 
because of the intense heat and thick black smoke, feared the death 
toll in the north-south Tauern tunnel would rise. It was the second 
deadly Alpine tunnel fire in just over two months. At least 100 
people were treated in hospitals, three of them in critical 
condition. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Asked To Resume Peace Talks  
</P>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Jordan and Lebanon urged Israel today to  
resume peace talks with its neighbors, saying a final regional 
settlement should ensure the right of Palestinians to an 
independent state. A statement issued at the end of talks between 
Jordan's King Abdullah and Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said 
Israel's negotiations with Syria and Lebanon ``should resume from 
where they broke off'' in 1996. During his one-day stay in Jordan, 
Lahoud laid a wreathe at the tomb of the late King Hussein, who 
died of cancer last February. 

</P>
<P>
	New Nigerian Leader Takes Office  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Promising that ``we shall not fail,''  
Olusegun Obasanjo today became Nigeria's first civilian president 
in 15 years, ending a string of disastrous military regimes that 
crippled this African giant. Thousands of spectators cheered as 
Obasanjo embraced the outgoing military ruler, Gen. Abdulsalami 
Abubakar, who guided the 11-month transition that brought Nigeria 
from brutal dictatorship to democracy. Obasanjo pledged to rebuild 
a nation left in squalor despite billions of dollars in oil wealth. 

</P>
<P>
	Mark Martin Wins Carquest 300  
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Mark Martin won his NASCAR Busch Grand  
National series-leading fourth race in eight starts this year, 
holding off Dale Earnhardt Jr. in the Carquest Auto Parts 300 
today. Martin led 108 of the 200 laps, including the final 38 
circuits around Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte. He wound up 
about six car-lengths ahead of Earnhardt after the two staged a 
tight duel over the last 30 laps. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Stun Cardinals in the Ninth  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Glenallen Hill tied the game with a pinch-hit  
homer in the ninth and Mark Grace won it minutes later with a 
run-scoring double as the Chicago Cubs rallied to stun the St. 
Louis Cardinals 4-3 today. The Cardinals, playing without Mark 
McGwire, who stayed at the team hotel to treat an infected corn on 
his right foot, took a 3-2 lead into the ninth. But with one out, 
Hill hit his seventh career pinch-hit homer. Jose Hernandez then 
singled to left and raced around with the winning run when Grace 
drove a double into the right field corner. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
