<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Doctors Vote To Unionize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hundreds of doctors employed by Los Angeles  
County voted to unionize and become part of a growing number of 
physicians across the nation who are joining the ranks of organized 
labor. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote on Friday was the largest union election for  
post-residency physicians in 18 years, organizers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 790 county doctors, many of whom care for the poor and  
uninsured, joined the Union of American Physicians and Dentists on 
a 341 to 182 vote, or 65 percent to 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're basically concerned with how health care is being  
provided,'' said Janice Nelson, a physician at Los Angeles 
County-USC Medical Center. ``Doctors are frustrated with managed 
care and being dictated to by bean counters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	County officials, who remained neutral during the three-year  
organizing campaign, said they will begin contract talks as soon as 
they are requested. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no idea what they're going to ask for in their  
contract,'' said Rhonda Albey, a labor relations administrator for 
Los Angeles County. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 of the doctors are affiliated with the area's  
three medical schools that operate county hospitals. Others work 
for the county jail, coroner and public health clinics. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 45,000 doctors nationwide -- about 6 percent -- belong  
to unions. That's up from about 25,000 two years ago. The Union of 
American Physicians now represents about 6,000 post-residency 
doctors, or those who have completed their last stage of medical 
training. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend stems from the growing influence of health maintenance  
organizations and the belief that administrators have assumed too 
much influence over patient care, the doctors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson said money was not the driving issue behind Friday's  
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody works for the county in the public sector in order to  
get rich,'' she said. ``We work because we have a commitment to 
take care of the poor and the uninsured of the county.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The county doctors said they want more say in the care of  
patients and in the construction of a new hospital to replace the 
earthquake-damaged County-USC hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Make no mistake about this, we are going to preserve a  
doctor's prerogative to prescribe and deliver the best treatments 
for patients,'' said Robert Weinmann, UAPD president and a San Jose 
neurologist. 
</P>
<P>
	The last major organizing effort was in August 1981, when 1,300  
doctors employed by the state of California voted to join the 
physicians' union. The UAPD is affiliated with the American 
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
