<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Kept Out of Cubs' Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Mark McGwire was forced out of the St. Louis  
Cardinals' lineup Saturday with an infected corn on his right foot. 
</P>
<P>
	The painful condition kept baseball's single-season home run  
champ from even coming to Wrigley Field. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire was initially examined by Cubs physician Dr. John  
Marquardt and will be checked again to determine if he will be able 
to play in the series finale Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He developed a cellulitis from a soft corn he has on his right  
foot. It's in between his last two toes,'' Cardinals trainer Barry 
Weinberg said before Saturday's game, adding that McGwire will 
remain at the team hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	``It develops during the course of each season and he manages  
it, but it got infected. We got to keep him off his foot for a day 
and he's on a lot of antibiotics. We're optimistic for tomorrow and 
that's why we're keeping him in bed today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, who hit 70 homers last season, went 0-for-4 with two  
strikeouts Friday in his first head-to-head matchup this season 
with Chicago's Sammy Sosa, who hit 66 homers a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals manager Tony La Russa said the corn had nothing to do  
with McGwire's performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was sore before the game up into his leg, which is the  
infection. But it wasn't anything to do with his at-bats,'' La 
Russa said. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire has 14 homers this season, including six in his previous  
nine games. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli Marrero replaced McGwire at first base.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
