<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Salvador 2, Colombia 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Second-half substitute Vladimir  
Montes scored the tying goal and set up the game winner by Ronald 
Cerritos to lead El Salvador to a 2-1 win over Colombia in an 
exhibition game at Giants Stadium on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Hector Hurtado scored for favored Colombia, which was missing  
several of its regulars due to club commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombians came close to tying the game a handful of times  
in the final 10-15 minutes, but they were either stopped by 
goalkeeper Sergio Munoz or they missed the net with shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Frustration boiled over in injury time when several players on  
both sides entangled in a shoving match, eliciting boos and 
whistles from many in the crowd of 43,192. The Colombian players 
exited the field quickly, many failing to participate in the 
customary handshake. 
</P>
<P>
	Montes tied the game in the 47th minutes on a play that started  
with a long throw-in by Roberto Hernandez. Cerritos of the San Jose 
Clash of the MLS flicked the ball with his head in the penalty area 
and Montes scissor-kicked the ball past goalkeeper Agustin Julio. 
</P>
<P>
	The game-winner came in the 63rd minute when Nelson Flores sent  
a long ball from the left wing across the area to the end line. 
Montes leaped to head the ball back into play and Cerritos ran onto 
it, slamming it into the back of the net. Agustin never had a 
chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia dominated play in the first half and El Salvador was  
lucky to be trailing only 1-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurtado scored for the Colombians in the 24th minute, but they  
had at least three other good scoring opportunities. The best one 
came just at the start of injury time when Fredy Grisales dribbled 
past two defenders in the penalty box, then put his shot just wide 
of the far post with Munoz at his mercy. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurtado's goal came on a shot that bounced off the far post and  
into the net. It was set up when he ran onto a through ball and 
chipped it over a sliding Munoz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
