<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 00:51:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Envoy Says Peace Talks Progressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A Russian envoy says he made enough  
progress in talks with Slobodan Milosevic to be virtually certain 
of returning to Yugoslavia next week for a new round. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Viktor Chernomyrdin wrapped up nine hours of  
face-to-face talks with Milosevic on Friday, declaring that the 
Yugoslav president was the key to a Kosovo peace plan despite his 
indictment for war crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after the talks, NATO unleashed another wave of airstrikes  
targeting Yugoslavia's power supply system. Local media reported 
that intense NATO attacks early today caused a massive power 
outage, extensive damage in several towns and injuries to four 
civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin again urged a pause in NATO's bombing campaign to  
give peace talks a chance, and said he was ``very satisfied'' with 
the talks despite no signs of a breakthrough, Russia's ITAR-Tass 
news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	A source close to the Yugoslav government also called the  
outcome of the talks ``positive,'' but did not elaborate. 
Milosevic, however, gave little sign he was ready to meet NATO 
demands. 
</P>
<P>
	His office issued a statement reiterating that Yugoslavia  
accepts the general principles of a plan sketched out in early May 
by Russia and the world's top seven industrialized countries, the 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	It added that it wants the U.N. Security Council to be empowered  
to handle ``the entire problem'' -- a phrase that indicates 
Milosevic may be more willing than before to accept a Security 
Council agreement to end the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia and China have vetoes in the council and are unlikely to  
accept anything vehemently opposed by Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Western nations have rejected a similar offer from Milosevic  
because he would not agree to aspects of the plan calling for a 
total withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo and the deployment of a 
well-armed international security force. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin said Russian military experts traveling with him  
had discussed with their Yugoslav counterparts conditions of a 
pullout of Yugoslav army and police troops from Kosovo and the 
introduction of an international contingent under the U.N. flag. 
</P>
<P>
	In talks in Moscow today, Chernomyrdin is expected to brief two  
other key envoys in the crisis -- Finnish President Martti 
Ahtisaari, the European Union representative, and Strobe Talbott, 
the deputy U.S. secretary of state. 
</P>
<P>
	But as Chernomyrdin left, NATO jets hit hard on Yugoslavia's  
power supply system and on suspected military and other targets. 
</P>
<P>
	Power plants Drmno, 40 miles east of Belgrade, and Bajina Basta  
in the west of the country were hit shortly after midnight, radio 
stations Studio B and Pancevo reported. Much of Serbia was left 
without electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	In Novi Sad, the second-largest city, missiles struck near the  
already wrecked building of state-run Serbian television. Several 
nearby private homes were badly damaged and two civilians were 
hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	In the town of Cuprija, 75 miles southeast of Belgrade, NATO  
missiles struck the city center in a pre-dawn attack, the private 
Beta news agency reported. Two people were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The official Tanjug news agency reported six powerful explosions  
northwest of Belgrade, on Mount Fruska Gora and near the town of 
Sremska Mitrovica. Batajnica military airfield, a frequent NATO 
target just outside Belgrade, was also hit. 
</P>
<P>
	More NATO attacks were reported in Kosovo, a province in Serbia,  
the dominant republic of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	A Serb army commander for the province, Maj. Gen. Vladimir  
Lazarevic, accused NATO of siding with the independence-minded 
Kosovo Liberation Army, Beta reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazarevic lambasted the alliance for ``directly assisting  
efforts by armed groups of (ethnic) Albanian terrorists to 
penetrate Yugoslav territory,'' from neighboring Albania, and 
described the attempts as ``a new phase of aggression'' against 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of refugees, meanwhile, poured into Albania despite  
fighting between Serb forces and the KLA along the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 450 ethnic Albanians entered at the main Morini border  
crossing from Kosovo on Friday, according to the Organization for 
Security and Cooperation in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
