<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fusion 2, Mutiny 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- The Miami Fusion, behind goals by  
Diego Serna and Henry Gutierrez, snapped a five-game losing streak 
tonight with a 2-1 victory over the Tampa Bay Mutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay (5-5, 9 points) had its five-game winning streak  
snapped as it suffered its first loss since acquiring Carlos 
Valderrama from the Fusion on April 23. 
</P>
<P>
	The win moved the Fusion (4-8, 8 points) into a three-way tie  
with New England and New York/New Jersey for fourth place in Major 
League Soccer's Eastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Valderrama received an ovation from Fusion fans during pregame  
introductions. He was booed, though, in the 37th minute after 
receiving a yellow card for blatantly elbowing Serna as the two 
went for a ball near midfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Serna opened the scoring in the 22nd minute, when he headed a  
Gutierrez cross past Mutiny goalkeeper Andy Kirk. The goal gave the 
Fusion its first lead in a game since a 1-0 win over Kansas City on 
April 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Serna now has scored a goal in four straight games and has seven  
on the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez gave the Fusion a 2-0 lead in the 56th minute with a  
penalty kick goal. Referee Brian Hall awarded the penalty after 
Tampa Bay defender Dominic Kinnear fouled Fusion forward Mickey 
Trotman as he jumped for a Serna cross. 
</P>
<P>
	Valderrama made it 2-1 in the 58th minute with a header on a  
Steve Ralston cross. The goal, Valderrama's first with the Mutiny, 
snapped a 271-minute scoreless streak for Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Kinnear nearly equalized in the 68th minute with a shot from 22  
yards that forced a diving save from Miami goalkeeper Jeff Cassar. 
A minute later, Mauricio Ramos hit the post from 25 yards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
