<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheel Tethers Work Fine at Motorola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Ill. (AP) -- So far, so good for CART's new wheel  
tethers. 
</P>
<P>
	Robby Gordon was the guinea pig for the new safety measure  
designed to prevent fan injuries in the stands, when his car spun 
out at the bottom of turn 3 in the 11th lap of Saturday's Motorola 
300. The left front tire was knocked loose in the resulting 
collision, but it the tether helped keep it from flying off. 
</P>
<P>
	The first test was also the first in a series of successes as  
the tethers held fast all day. When Patrick Carpentier and Bryan 
Herta got sandwiched in turn 1 and ended up in the wall, in fact, 
nothing came loose. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appeared like the tethers did the job and kept things close  
to the car,'' said team owner John Menard. ``We're just very 
unhappy we had to be the first guys to test them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon thought so, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't seem like it hurt our crash,'' he said. ``I think  
it'll be a good thing for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tethers were added in the wake of a crash during an Indy  
Racing League event on May 1 in Concord, N.C., where three fans 
were killed and eight injured by a wheel and suspension parts. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Gordon's future, he bruised his right calf but expects to  
compete in the second half of his weekend double Sunday in the 
Indianapolis 500. He pronounced himself good to go after a 
less-than-strenuous test shortly after the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``I drove my golf cart back from the medical trailer to our  
garage, so I guess that means I'm fine,'' Gordon said. ``The bigger 
issue for me is trying to figure out what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon is one of three drivers attempting doubles this weekend,  
with Roberto Moreno also running Motorola and Indy. Moreno, subbing 
for Mark Blundell on Saturday, was fourth. Tony Stewart plans on 
running both Indy and the NASCAR Coca-Cola 500 the same day. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	WHAT TEAMWORK?: For the second straight year, Team Kool Green  
drivers Paul Tracy and Dario Franchitti tangled. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the two knocked each other out on the first lap. This  
time, Tracy cut Franchitti off after Franchitti tried to pass on 
the inside in turn 1 on the 147th lap. Tracy spun into the wall, 
but Franchitti somehow escaped damage after their wheels touched. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Tracy was second and Franchitti was third. Somehow,  
team owner Barry Green didn't sound incensed about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those racing incidents,'' Green said. ``The two of  
them got together and just touched. It's too bad, because they were 
both running well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for the drivers involved, Tracy's initial reaction: ``Well,  
I'm not very happy right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, who recovered and finished third, said avoiding  
contact with the wall or another car was perhaps his greatest 
driving feat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, it was the worst slide I've ever been in without  
hitting something solid,'' Franchitti said. ``We'll sort it out 
tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	PIT PERILS: A member of Gil de Ferran's pit crew had a rough day  
on the job. David Stephens sustained a concussion when an air gun 
popped off a wheel and smacked him in the head hard enough to crack 
his helmet during a pit stop on lap 36. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephens was conscious when he was air-lifted to Saint Louis  
University Hospital in St. Louis for a CAT scan. 
</P>
<P>
	In conventional injury news:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Patrick Carpentier, who was knocked out of the race along with  
Bryan Herta on lap 114, complained of neck pain and was taken for 
precautionary X-rays. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Tarso Marques spun and hit the wall in turn 4 on lap 32. He  
left the car under his own power but was subsequently air-lifted to 
Saint Louis University Hospital for a precautionary CAT scan. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRIEFLY: Christian Fittipaldi, who finished ninth, is the only  
CART driver to complete every lap in the season's first six races. 
Fittipaldi is Andretti's teammate on the Newman-Haas racing team. 
... Herta on getting squeezed and knocked out of the race when four 
cars entered turn 1 on lap 114: ``I saw a green car dive-bomb 
underneath me. The next thing I knew, I was sideways and into the 
wall.'' ... Andretti has led for 290 laps, or 40.5 percent, the 
first three years of the Motorola 300. ... Gateway International 
added about 20,000 seats for a capacity of 70,000, but the stands 
were only about half full. The major reason probably is that 
Indianapolis is only 250 miles east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
