<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's top drug authority says  
Colombian cartels are using native people in the Amazon jungle to 
transport drugs, a newspaper reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-drug Secretary Walter Maierovitch said Indians carry drugs  
from Brazil to refineries in Colombia, the Jornal do Brasil 
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maierovitch spoke at a meeting this week between Brazilian and  
Colombian authorities to discuss drug-trafficking in the Amazon, 
the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials drew up a report that will be the basis for an  
agreement on combatting trafficking to be signed in July. Peru also 
will be asked to sign. The report called Brazil's border region 
lawless, blaming a failure by authorities to promote economic and 
social development, the daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil is installing a $1.2 billion Amazon Surveillance System,  
which uses radar and aircraft to combat trafficking, as well as 
forest burning and illegal gold mining. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- President Andres Pastrana appointed a  
former running mate as defense minister Saturday, filling a spot 
left empty this week by a resignation that highlighted military 
reservations about peace talks with leftist rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Luis Fernando Ramirez, 40, who was the Conservative Party's  
vice-presidential candidate during Pastrana's unsuccessful 1994 bid 
for the presidency, will replace Rodrigo Lloreda, the presidential 
press office announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Lloreda said he resigned to protest Pastrana's refusal to put  
time limits on a military evacuation of a southern region where 
peace talks began in January with Colombia's most powerful 
guerrilla group. 
</P>
<P>
	Army officials say the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia  
are exploiting the situation to step up military preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastrana's government maintains the troop pullout is a necessary  
concession to facilitate negotiations to end the 35-year armed 
conflict, which has left tens of thousands dead. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Presbyterian minister Jaime  
Wright, a leading defender of human rights during Brazil's 1964-85 
military dictatorship, died of a heart attack Saturday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright died at his home in Vitoria, 315 miles northeast of Rio,  
TV Globo reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Together with Roman Catholic Cardinal Paulo Evaristo Arns, the  
former archbishop of Sao Paulo, Wright campaigned against violence 
and torture by the armed forces and led the project ``Brazil No 
More,'' which revealed the names of victims and torturers. 
</P>
<P>
	The military tried unsuccessfully to suppress the project, which  
won praise from the human rights group Amnesty International. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who retired in 1994, was to be buried in the state of  
Espirito Santo on Sunday, according to news reports. He is survived 
by a wife, four daughters and a son. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Spain's Banco Bilbao Viscaya has  
reached an agreement to buy Panama's Banco Ganadero from Banca 
Ganadero of Colombia, the institutions announced Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the purchase, which is pending approval by  
Panamanian banking officials, was not announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Banco Ganadero ended 1998 with assets equivalent to about $363  
million. It is one of more than 100 banks operating in Panama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
