<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Could Stall Auto Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Just minutes before James Hoffa entered  
the final days of negotiations to avert a Teamsters strike against 
17 trucking companies that haul cars to dealers' showrooms, he 
refused to rule out the possibility of a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless we can talk some sense into the heads of management, we  
have to shut the industry down. That's the classic idea of the only 
power we have,'' Hoffa said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators face a deadline of 12:01 a.m. Tuesday, when the  
contract expires. Earlier this month, the truckers authorized their 
negotiating committee to call a strike if talks fail. 
</P>
<P>
	The showdown is Hoffa's first test since he became president of  
the Teamsters in March, assuming a post once held by his late 
father, Jimmy Hoffa. This is James Hoffa's first negotiation as 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Ian Hunter said today it was too soon to talk about a strike.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think both parties are committed to finding a resolution.  
This is just typical collective bargaining, rhetoric aside,'' he 
said today as he entered the room for his first round of talks with 
Hoffa. 
</P>
<P>
	A strike could throw a roadblock in front of the auto industry's  
record sales pace. So far this year, U.S. sales of new cars and 
light trucks are up 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters contract covers about 12,000 drivers, mechanics,  
yard and office workers nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	If a strike were called, industry officials expect the Teamsters  
initially would target just one of the major trucking companies 
that contract with automakers to move new cars to dealers from 
assembly plants, ports and rail yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Teamsters spokesman Chip Roth said Friday that the union could  
choose to strike some or all of the 17 trucking companies that are 
at the negotiating table. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters are seeking higher wages, improved pensions and  
health care, and a reduction in ``excessive work hours.'' They also 
are resisting proposals to pay lower salaries to entry-level 
drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Hunter said, automakers are pressing for lower prices  
from car haulers; labor costs have gone up 33 percent in the past 
four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our drivers are the highest paid in the trucking industry,''  
Hunter said. ``The average driver wage last year was $68,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers likely would use their own drivers and hire  
independents to help get some vehicles to dealers in the event of a 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're monitoring the situation closely,'' said Ford Motor Co.  
spokesman Ron Iori. ``We're hoping both the Teamsters and the 
haulers can reach a mutually agreeable situation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:41:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Ticket Offer Opens at Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australians received their first  
opportunity to buy a seat at the Sydney 2000 Olympic Games on 
Sunday when five million of the 9.6 million tickets went on sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The first of millions of copies of the Official Olympic Games  
Ticket Book was sent out with Sunday newspapers across the country. 
Buyers have 48 days to return order forms with full payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Ticket sales will give Sydney Olympic organizers a strong  
indication whether the International Olympic Committee corruption 
scandals have curtailed interest in next year's Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Popular events such as the opening and closing ceremonies,  
swimming finals and some track and field, gymnastics and basketball 
sessions are expected to be oversubscribed, with a random ballot 
used to decide who gets tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	The ticket books, inserted in News Ltd. newspapers under a  
sponsorship deal, are 52 pages long, including a day-by-day 
program, venue map and transport guides. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices range from $12.35 at sports such as rowing and baseball  
to $900 for the best seats at the opening and closing ceremonies. 
Seventy percent of all tickets will cost less than $39 and SOCOG 
aims to make $390 million from sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
