<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hoffa Leads Talks As Walkout Looms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Talks to avert a Teamsters strike against  
companies that haul new cars to dealers ended Saturday with little 
progress. Union President James P. Hoffa warned drivers are ready 
to walk when their contract expires at 12:01 a.m. EDT Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we have to call a strike, we will,'' Hoffa said before 4 1/2  
hours of closed-door bargaining failed to resolve the key issues. 
``Unless we can talk some sense into the heads of management, 
that's the only recourse a union has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The talks were to resume Sunday, again at a Virginia hotel near  
the union's Washington headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief management negotiator agreed that many matters were  
unresolved. But Ian Hunter of the National Automobile Transporters 
Association added, ``There's no need to be concerned yet. This is 
typical collective bargaining, rhetoric aside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations are an early test of Hoffa's leadership of the  
union once led by his late father, Jimmy Hoffa, before the elder 
Hoffa was sent to prison in 1967 for jury-tampering and fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	James P. Hoffa, a labor lawyer, took over in March, winning an  
election held after a campaign finance scandal had ousted the 
incumbent. Hoffa joined the car-hauling talks for the first time 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters contract covering about 12,000 drivers, mechanics,  
yard and office workers nationwide expires at 12:01 a.m. EDT 
Tuesday. Union members earlier this month authorized their 
negotiating team to call a strike if talks failed. 
</P>
<P>
	In this robust economy, a Teamster strike of more than a few  
days could put a dent in auto sales on pace for record this year. 
The big-rig drivers move 95 percent of new cars to the nation's 
showrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	The union could target one or all of the 17 major trucking  
companies that contract with automakers to move new cars to dealers 
from assembly plants, ports and rail yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers have said they would use their own drivers and hire  
independents to help get some vehicles to dealers in the event of a 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The sticking point appears to be an industry proposal for a  
wage-scale giving entry-level drivers lower salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could never tolerate a two-tier pay scale. That's a  
strikeable issue,'' Hoffa said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not afraid of a strike because our people have been  
working hard and I know that the industry is making record profits. 
There's never been a better time for us to get our piece of the 
pie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teamsters also want better pensions and health care, higher wage  
increases than management is offering and fewer hours on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffa has promised members major pension breakthroughs in this  
contract, said Ken Paff of Teamsters for a Democratic Union, the 
group that supported Hoffa's opponent in the last election. 
</P>
<P>
	``In that sense, it's being watched nationally,'' Paff said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hoffa would not discuss details of any strike plan.  
</P>
<P>
	Car haulers say Teamsters are the highest-paid truckers at  
$68,000 on average. On Friday, the companies released a study 
concluding that labor costs are rising faster than what the hauling 
companies can charge automakers. Labor costs have gone up 33 
percent in the past four years, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
