<DOCNO> APW19990529.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 03:01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *David Paul Kane    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kennedy, Cabot &AMP; Co. founder David Paul Kane,  
who named his discount brokerage after John F. Kennedy to appeal to 
Democrats and Henry Cabot Lodge to lure Republicans, died Tuesday 
from complications of a stroke. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Kane was a former lobster importer and car wash owner who made a  
fortune in the discount brokerage business. He also broadcast stock 
market commentaries for two decades on local KWHY-TV. 
</P>
<P>
	He sold the remainder of his interest in Kennedy, Cabot &AMP; Co. in  
1997 for $155 million to Waterhouse Investor Services Inc., the New 
York brokerage arm of Canadian banking giant Toronto-Dominion. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Ed Peterson    	
</P>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Ed Peterson, inventor of the alarm that  
beeps to warn people when trucks and heavy machinery are backing 
up, died Wednesday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson also invented collapsible luggage carriers, home  
security alarms and automotive electrical devices. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mid-1960s, he invented the Bac-A-Larm, marketing it  
initially to international construction and engineering giant 
Morrison Knudsen Corp., which, like Peterson's company, was based 
in Boise. 
</P>
<P>
	The system is used worldwide now, and the company he founded  
with his brother, Peterson Rebuild and Exchange Co., or Preco Inc. 
as it is known today, is the world's largest supplier of reverse 
warning systems. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Charles F. McErlean Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) -- Charles F. McErlean Sr., former president  
of United Airlines' parent company, UAL Inc., has died. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with a Georgetown University law degree and a background  
with the National Labor Relations Board, McErlean was hired in 1945 
by W.A. Patterson, founder of United Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	He started the company's legal department and held several jobs  
in the next few decades, including vice president, senior vice 
president and member of the company's board of directors. He rose 
to United vice chairman and UAL president. 
</P>
<P>
	McErlean was considered a strong administrator who played an  
active role in labor negotiations over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	He died May 21 in his Oak Brook home. Funeral services were  
planned Saturday in Our Lady's Chapel at Mayslake Village in Oak 
Brook. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 06:34:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI WorldCom Buying SkyTel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Days after MCI WorldCom Inc. shot down rumors it  
was planning to buy pager company Skytel Communications Inc., it 
did just that, announcing a $1.3 billion stock acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's No. 2 long-distance phone company will pay stock  
worth $21.24 for each share of SkyTel, filling a gaping wireless 
hole in an otherwise broad list of telecommunications businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom, a major owner of the circuitry that makes up the  
Internet, will also absorb about $525 million in debt from SkyTel, 
which is one of the few profitable companies in the paging 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, shares of SkyTel shot higher after an Internet  
service named Company Sleuth reported that MCI WorldCom had 
reserved the Web site domain name ``skytelworldcom.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom quickly played down the significance of that move,  
saying it routinely reserves domain names that might have value, 
and that the registration for the SkyTel-related name was the work 
of an overzealous employee. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement announced Friday comes amid a frenzy of  
deal-making that's reshaping the communications industry, with 
phone companies like Bell Atlantic and GTE merging and AT&AMP;T 
spending about $100 billion on cable TV properties it plans to use 
for phone calls and Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	For MCI WorldCom, the SkyTel deal comes after two failed  
attempts to buy its way into the $33 billion wireless 
communications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Just weeks ago, talks to acquire Nextel Communications, the  
largest independent wireless company, unraveled after the companies 
failed to agree on price. In January, MCI WorldCom dropped out of a 
bidding war to buy AirTouch Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see a lot of opportunity for growth in the overall wireless  
market, and over time, we expect to be a broader participant in 
that market,'' said Frank Walter, a spokesman for MCI WorldCom. 
</P>
<P>
	SkyTel and MCI WorldCom, both based in Mississippi, have  
long-standing business ties. MCI WorldCom is the largest reseller 
of the SkyTel's messaging services. 
</P>
<P>
	SkyTel, with about 1.6 million customers, has been a leader in  
the move toward two-way pagers that enable customers to exchange 
messages directly with other pagers or via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, expected to be completed in six to nine months, was  
announced after the close of financial markets Friday. Shares of 
SkyTel rose $1 to $20.31 1/4, while shares of MCI WorldCom rose $1.43 3/4 
a share to $86.37 1/2, both on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 06:28:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Discovery Docks With Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) -- In another milestone for the new  
international space station, shuttle Discovery docked with the 
outpost early today for six days of activities that include a 
spacewalk, repair work and supply transfers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've made the first docking with space station look  
effortless, and you've set the standard for all those who follow,'' 
Mission Control told Discovery's astronauts after they successfully 
linked the two spacecraft at 12:24 a.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	With shuttle commander Kent Rominger at the controls, Discovery  
pulled up and latched on to the space station as it soared 240 
miles above the border of Russia and Kazakstan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have capture!'' exclaimed Rominger.  
</P>
<P>
	The seven-member crew is the first to journey to the outpost  
since December, when astronauts delivered an American module and 
joined it with a Russian component already in orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been six months since anyone came to visit,'' Mission  
Control said. ``Welcome aboard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole station looks beautiful, and we're happy to be  
visiting,'' replied astronaut Daniel Barry. 
</P>
<P>
	The astronauts entered an outer chamber of the station this  
morning to collect air samples. To get things ready, ground 
controllers cranked up the heat toward room temperature. Normally, 
the station is about 25 degrees when no one is there. 
</P>
<P>
	The crew will venture all the way inside the outpost for the  
first time Sunday, when they begin their maintenance work and start 
transferring two tons of supplies into the station. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, Barry and astronaut Tamara Jernigan were to perform  
a spacewalk starting late tonight to attach tool bags and cranes to 
the outside of the station. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the gear to be left inside are computers, tools, water and  
clothes for the station's first permanent inhabitants, who are 
supposed to move in next March. Their arrival has been delayed 
because of the Russians' inability to complete a component that 
will double as living quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the absence of the Russian component -- it should have  
gone up last year -- Saturday's docking had to be revamped. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers devised a plan in which the station's large thrusters  
were turned off and small thrusters were used to hold the station 
steady during Discovery's slow and cautious approach Friday night. 
The moment the docking rings on the two spacecraft touched, Russian 
controllers sent a command to shut down all of the station 
thrusters. 
</P>
<P>
	Space shuttles have docked nine times with Russia's Mir station  
in recent years. But this marked the first time since Skylab in the 
mid-1970s that NASA docked with its own space station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 06:28:50 </DATE_TIME>
