<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forrest Sawyer Leaving ABC News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Emmy award-winning TV news correspondent Forrest  
Sawyer, who regularly sat in for Ted Koppel on ``Nightline'' and 
Peter Jennings on ``ABC World News Tonight,'' is leaving the 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	The move follows an even higher profile ABC news departure.  
Earlier this month Hugh Downs announced he was leaving ``20/20'' 
after 21 years on the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Sawyer was unable to reach an agreement with the network on a  
new contract, the New York Post reported Saturday. The newsman was 
not reached for comment, but the network confirmed his departure, 
saying it was not part of eight to 10 cuts planned for ABC on-air 
personalities. 
</P>
<P>
	``His leaving has everything to do with the fact that Forrest  
decided that the time was right for him to move on and look 
elsewhere for other opportunities,'' said spokeswoman Eileen 
Murphy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sawyer most recently filed reports on the Kosovo refugee crisis  
in Albania and on problems with the Apache attack helicopter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 08:01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charismatic Could Have Been Had </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Right from the start, breeder Tom Roach thought  
the chestnut colt had the look of being something special. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Fame trainer D. Wayne Lukas also saw promise, but he  
couldn't bring it out. 
</P>
<P>
	What owner Bob Lewis saw was a poor investment.  
</P>
<P>
	``He is a chow hound,'' Lewis said. ``He eats all the time.''  
</P>
<P>
	But in the last two months, Charismatic has paid his feed bill --  
and then some. 
</P>
<P>
	Should he win the Belmont Stakes June 5 and become the first  
Triple Crown champion in 21 years, he would earn $600,000 from the 
purse plus a $5 million bonus for sweeping the Kentucky Derby, 
Preakness and Belmont. That would push his bankroll to more than 
$6.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, however, Charismatic had eaten his way out of  
Lewis' favor. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas ran him in a claiming race for a $62,500 pricetag at Santa  
Anita. At that time, anyone with that amount could have bought 
Charismatic, although Lukas did not want to see the horse 
purchased. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shared Wayne's feeling, but if we lost him, we'd have been  
very happy to get the $62,500. The horse was costing us money,'' 
Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Racing, after all, is a business, and even when you own a  
moneymaker like 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Silver 
Charm, as Lewis and his wife Beverly do, you still try to cut your 
losses. The Lewises bought Charismatic for $200,000 as a weanling, 
and the ink in his ledger was redder than his chestnut coat. 
</P>
<P>
	The colt with the four white socks and the oval star and  
connected thin stripe on his face is by Summer Squall, the 1990 
Kentucky Derby runner-up and Preakness winner, out of Bali Babe. 
Secretariat and Northern Dancer are his paternal great grand sires, 
and Secretariat's sire and dam, Bold Ruler and Somethingroyal, are 
on both sides of his pedigree. 
</P>
<P>
	He was foaled in March 1996 and weaned that November at Parish  
Hill Farm of Dr. Ben Roach and his son, Tom, who bought Bali Babe 
about eight years ago at the Keeneland November sale. Summer Squall 
stands at William S. Farish's Lane's End Farm. 
</P>
<P>
	The solidly built colt -- Lukas estimated he still weighed about  
1,200 pounds at the Preakness -- takes after his parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Of Bali Babe, Tom Roach said, ``She looks like she could pull a  
beer wagon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That, however, is not why Charismatic was bought by Lewis, owner  
of the biggest beer distributorship in Southern California. He 
bought him on the recommendations of trainer-bloodstock agent Tom 
Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was one of the best-looking weanlings I've ever seen,'' Tom  
Roach said. ``We thought he was going to be an outstanding colt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After only one win in his first nine starts, however,  
Charismatic ended up in that Feb. 11 claiming race. He finished 
second, but he got the win when the first-place finisher was 
disqualified. 
</P>
<P>
	He also did not get claimed.  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said that when the race was over Lukas told him, ``I think  
we got away with one there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, it turned out to be the second time Lewis and Lukas  
got lucky. The colt's first win in his fifth start also was for a 
$62,500 tag Nov. 21, 1998, at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic's next start after Feb. 11 was a second in an  
allowance Feb. 19 at Santa Anita. He then finished second in the El 
Camino Real Derby March 6 at Bay Meadows and was fourth in the 1 
1-8-mile Santa Anita Derby April 3. Lukas then decided to send the 
colt to Kentucky, but it was the 1 1-2-mile Belmont Stakes he was 
pointing him for, not the 1 1-4-mile Derby or 1 3-16-mile 
Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told Bob and Beverly prior to the Kentucky Derby, `I don't  
know about the first two, but we'll look good in the Belmont -- I 
just like his style,''' Lukas said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was after the Santa Anita Derby that Lukas unlocked the key  
to success for Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	The key, Lewis said, is that Charismatic ``thrives on work. He  
thrives on racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the colt holds his weight -- horses usually lose weight  
during a campaign -- Lewis said Lukas told him he was going to have 
to work him hard before the Derby. Instead, Lukas entered 
Charismatic in the 1 1-16-mile Lexington, which he won at Keeneland 
in stakes-record time two weeks after the Santa Anita Derby and two 
weeks before the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't push the right buttons,'' Lukas said. ``I probably in  
my career never misjudged a horse early on as I did this one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not only was Charismatic suddenly earning his keep -- his  
earnings were some $300,000 after the Lexington -- the Lewises also 
were back in the Kentucky Derby picture. 
</P>
<P>
	At the beginning of the year, they had early Derby favorite,  
Exploit, trained by Bob Baffert, who trained Silver Charm and Real 
Quiet. Then, in losing for the first time in six starts in the San 
Felipe on March 13 at Santa Anita, Exploit chipped a bone in a knee 
and was retired. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises then pinned their hopes on the Baffert-trained  
Straight Man, but that colt ran poorly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't really looking for anyone (for the Triple Crown  
races), and Wayne came up with Charismatic,'' Bob Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Overlooking Charismatic is what handicappers and bettors did in  
the Derby. Charismatic's winning mutuel of $64.60 was the third 
largest in the 125-year history of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the Preakness, Lukas told anybody who would listen,  
``Don't discredit the horse because I was foolish enough to run him 
in a claiming race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, however, was allowed to go off at 8-1 in the  
Preakness, making him the longest-priced Derby winner to start that 
race since Dark Star finished fifth in 1953. 
</P>
<P>
	He might not even be the favorite in the Belmont, which could  
have as many as 14 starters. His odds should be much shorter, 
however, if for no other reason than the Roach family and friends 
betting on him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have about 1,000 people there,'' Tom Roach joked.  
``We've heard from people we haven't heard from in 30 or 40 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ex-claimer certainly will be the sentimental choice as he  
tries to become only the 12th Triple Crown winner. 
</P>
<P>
	And that would be quite a movie script: From chow hound to  
charismatic champion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 09:31:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Questions About Gas Spike Persist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- As the Memorial Day weekend kicks off the  
summer driving season, supply shortages blamed for the biggest, 
fastest gasoline price spike in U.S. history are in retreat. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices are falling nationwide in a trend that is expected to  
continue for several weeks as fire-damaged refineries in California 
return to normal operation and world markets work through a glut of 
crude oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, for motorists and some public officials, a big question  
remains. Were drivers gouged by the oil companies when prices shot 
up so high and so fast during March and early April? 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission and the California attorney general  
are trying to answer that question with separate investigations of 
gasoline prices in California, the nation's most populous state. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigations focus on a price spiral that sent U.S. retail  
gasoline prices up 23 cents per gallon on average between March 5 
and April 9. In California, the increase was even sharper: a 
45-cent climb to $1.60, according to the Lundberg Letter, a 
newsletter that analyzes oil and gasoline markets. The full-service 
price for premium rose to nearly $2 in some parts of Northern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, the jump was faster and steeper than any other,  
including price increases that followed Iraq's invasion of Kuwait 
in 1990 and the Arab oil embargo in 1974, said Trilby Lundberg, 
publisher of the Lundberg Survey, a bimonthly review of gasoline 
prices. But it followed more than a year of historically low prices 
resulting from weak demand and an oversupply of crude. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry has not insisted on making a handsome profit at  
the retail level,'' said Lundberg. ``They are crazed price 
cutters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What bothers investigators is that as retail prices rose,  
California refineries gross revenues -- which include operating 
costs that can fluctuate widely -- rose on average from 27 cents per 
gallon of gasoline to 70 cents per gallon, according to California 
Energy Commission figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far there hasn't been an adequate explanation from the oil  
industry as to the causes of the price spike,'' said California 
Attorney General Bill Lockyer. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the FTC said she could not comment on the  
direction of the probe or any preliminary findings. 
</P>
<P>
	In his investigation, Lockyer is not looking for criminal  
wrongdoing, but indications that the oil companies engaged in 
unfair business practices by boosting prices higher than their 
costs justified. If there is evidence of that, his office would 
consider filing a lawsuit seeking to force the companies to forfeit 
profits considered excessive. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar probes that have followed big price runups have failed  
to produce evidence of collusion or unfair pricing. Oil company 
officials contend that it is the market, not companies, that 
determines the price consumers pay at the pump. 
</P>
<P>
	``The marketplace is going to move up and move down. When you  
balance it all out it's still a tough business: low margins, very 
competitive,'' said Fred Gorrell, a spokesman for San 
Francisco-based Chevron Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``What refiners do is look at supply and demand and competition  
and we take the marketplace as we find it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	What oil companies found during March and April was a  
marketplace shaken by a remarkable chain of unrelated events. 
</P>
<P>
	In a matter of weeks:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Fires and transmission glitches caused four California  
refineries to curtail gasoline operation from Feb. 23 to March 23, 
leading to a 10 percent drop in overall production. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Five days later U.S. warplanes damaged a key Iraqi pumping  
station, raising fears of a drop in crude oil supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	--Two weeks after that, in an unusual display of resolve, OPEC  
members voted to cut production by 2.1 billion barrels per day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The price is still a bargain. We are not being badly  
treated,'' said Phil Berman, author of the Pump Price Report 
newsletter. ``Gasoline was underpriced before. Now prices are 
beginning to fall again. There's no sinister conspiracy here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
