<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Cancels Two Dozen Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways canceled two dozen  
flights today after growing numbers of pilots facing pay cuts and 
layoff threats called in sick to work, the airline said. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four flights were canceled today and the airline may  
cancel more later in the day, said Katherine Wang, Cathay's 
corporate communication manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong carrier also has stopped taking bookings since  
late Friday for flights flying in the next two weeks ``to ensure 
the situation is under control,'' Wang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who have already booked their flights are not affected,  
she said. Cathay has an average of 116 flights daily. 
</P>
<P>
	The carrier and its pilots have been locked in a dispute after  
it asked its senior pilots in March to take an 8 percent pay cut in 
exchange for stock options after Cathay suffered its first loss in 
35 years last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay lost $69 million last year.  
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Cathay halted nine weeks of talks with the pilots'  
union, the Hong Kong Aircrew Association, and offered a revised pay 
package, which included a smaller pay cut and better stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	The carrier is giving the pilots until noon on June 11 to decide  
whether to take a pay cut, retire early, or be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Some pilots, claiming they were too stressed because of the  
layoff threats, have been taking sick days. Hong Kong law allows 
pilots to stop flying because of stress. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials denied they had organized the action to force  
Cathay to reopen negotiations, but said they would not rule out 
future strike actions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are only urging them to go and see a doctor,'' said John  
Findlay, the union's secretary-general. ``If a pilot thinks he or 
she is unfit for duty, he or she is obliged'' to stop flying. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay officials refused to disclose any numbers, but Findlay  
said Friday that 40 to 50 pilots were absent from work that day, 
forcing Cathay to cancel four flights. He did not know how many 
pilots were out sick today. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang said passengers would be diverted to other flights with  
Cathay or other airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the impact on air traffic to the United States appeared  
minimal, with only a single flight canceled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
