<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Fret Over Farming Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the House bickers over a $61 billion  
agriculture spending bill, some lawmakers and industry analysts 
wonder how America's struggling farmers will react to the push to 
trim government programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Marcy Kaptur, the top Democrat on the House Appropriations  
subcommittee that sets farm spending levels, warned during floor 
debate last week that the fighting ``results in a negative message 
for agriculture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``One after another after another, it's like drip, drip, drip  
... every single sector is hemorrhaging and here we are nitpicking 
a bill that has come within budget,'' said Kaptur, D-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Rep. Terry Everett, R-Ala.: ``At a time when farmers are  
choosing whether they will sell their family farms ... it is 
incomprehensible. I'm just appalled at what's going on in this 
House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From Rep. Tom Latham, R-Iowa, came the plea, ``We have lived  
within our budget constraints. Please don't do this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives led by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., have made  
repeated attempts to cut the bill. They say they do not intend to 
hurt farmers but fear GOP leaders are bent on ignoring the budget's 
spending rules. 
</P>
<P>
	So far only one of the proposed cuts has passed -- $500,000 from  
the Agriculture Department's chief information officer's budget. 
But Coburn has said he has 115 amendments proposing millions in 
cuts, mostly from agricultural research programs. Farmers and their 
supporters contend the research is needed to improve crop yields 
and productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	The arguing on Capitol Hill comes amid farmers' continued  
struggle to deal with low commodity prices and lagging overseas 
demand for their products. Reducing government programs now would 
worsen the situation, some lawmakers say. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers did not appear to have immediate and strong reaction to  
the decision by GOP leaders to put the agriculture spending bill on 
hold after two days of debate last week. But that quietness may not 
last. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is so much posturing going on in the Congress that there  
is a tendency for people in this area. . . to discount such 
shenanigans,'' said Neil Harl, a professor at Iowa State 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was some raising of eyebrows but most did not consider  
it a serious threat to programs in the agricultural budget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Harl cautioned, ``Times are tough enough in most farm  
areas that any threat to appropriations is taken seriously.'' The 
spending bill's outcome could influence voting next year, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``History shows that when farmers are in deep economic and  
financial difficulty, they tend to vote less conservatively than 
when times are good so there is always that possibility,'' Harl 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Leland Swenson, president of the National Farmers Union, urged  
that the House ``wake up and begin to act in a constructive way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The economic pressures, the weather pressures and then to have  
on top of it these utterly ridiculous mannerisms in Washington 
really does send a negative message to the countryside,'' Swenson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a year ago, Congress passed a $6 billion bailout package to  
compensate for declining commodities and livestock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaptur, in a telephone interview Friday, said farmers may blame  
Congress for acting slowly during these tough times. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, acting on a request from March, Congress this month  
finally approved an emergency spending bill that included $153 
million to replenish farm loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers this week will begin receiving $2 billion in disaster  
payments that were approved in the October bailout. Agriculture 
Secretary Dan Glickman said the payments were delayed because the 
package was difficult to administer. 
</P>
<P>
	For farmers who had started spring planting by the time the  
latest aid comes through, the current debate in Congress might make 
them wonder if ``Congress is fiddling while Rome burns,'' Kaptur 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Syracuse Reaches Lacrosse Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Eighth-seeded Syracuse advanced to the  
NCAA Division I Lacrosse championship game for the 10th time 
Saturday, scoring six straight goals at the outset of the second 
half en route to a 13-9 upset of Georgetown. 
</P>
<P>
	Syracuse (12-4) held fifth-seeded Georgetown (13-3) scoreless  
for a span of 27 minutes, 17 seconds and outscored the Hoyas 6-0 in 
the pivotal third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orangemen will seek their seventh title Monday against the  
winner of Saturday's second semifinal game, between Johns Hopkins 
and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Syracuse, the first eighth-seeded team to reach the Final Four,  
avenged losses to Princeton, Loyola (Maryland) and Georgetown in 
the first three rounds of the tournament. Princeton was the 
three-time defending champion and Loyola's unbeaten season included 
a 10-8 win over Syracuse in April. 
</P>
<P>
	It was more of the same against Georgetown, which beat Syracuse  
17-13 just three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orangemen trailed 4-1 late in the first quarter before  
rallying to a 5-5 tie at halftime. Chris Cordisc then scored twice 
as Syracuse reeled off four successive goals in a span of 3 
minutes, 18 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Byrnes added his second goal of the game and Marc Alexander  
scored at 10:56 to make it 11-5. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 12-5 before Mike Kanach scored for Georgetown with 10:40  
left, the Hoyas' first goal since Andy Flick found the back of the 
net with 7:57 remaining in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown's Scott Urick recorded his third goal of the game to  
make it 12-7, but Matt Cutia responded with his third goal of the 
afternoon to clinch the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the 17th successive appearance in the Final Four by  
Syracuse and the first with John Desko as head coach. Desko served 
as an assistant under Roy Simmons, Jr. since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the two schools have an intense rivalry on the  
basketball court as members of the Big East, this was only their 
sixth meeting in lacrosse. Syracuse leads the series 4-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
