<HEADLINE>  Syracuse Reaches Lacrosse Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Eighth-seeded Syracuse advanced to the  
NCAA Division I Lacrosse championship game for the 10th time 
Saturday, scoring six straight goals at the outset of the second 
half en route to a 13-9 upset of Georgetown. 
</P>
<P>
	Syracuse (12-4) held fifth-seeded Georgetown (13-3) scoreless  
for a span of 27 minutes, 17 seconds and outscored the Hoyas 6-0 in 
the pivotal third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orangemen will seek their seventh title Monday against the  
winner of Saturday's second semifinal game, between Johns Hopkins 
and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Syracuse, the first eighth-seeded team to reach the Final Four,  
avenged losses to Princeton, Loyola (Maryland) and Georgetown in 
the first three rounds of the tournament. Princeton was the 
three-time defending champion and Loyola's unbeaten season included 
a 10-8 win over Syracuse in April. 
</P>
<P>
	It was more of the same against Georgetown, which beat Syracuse  
17-13 just three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orangemen trailed 4-1 late in the first quarter before  
rallying to a 5-5 tie at halftime. Chris Cordisc then scored twice 
as Syracuse reeled off four successive goals in a span of 3 
minutes, 18 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Byrnes added his second goal of the game and Marc Alexander  
scored at 10:56 to make it 11-5. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 12-5 before Mike Kanach scored for Georgetown with 10:40  
left, the Hoyas' first goal since Andy Flick found the back of the 
net with 7:57 remaining in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown's Scott Urick recorded his third goal of the game to  
make it 12-7, but Matt Cutia responded with his third goal of the 
afternoon to clinch the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the 17th successive appearance in the Final Four by  
Syracuse and the first with John Desko as head coach. Desko served 
as an assistant under Roy Simmons, Jr. since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the two schools have an intense rivalry on the  
basketball court as members of the Big East, this was only their 
sixth meeting in lacrosse. Syracuse leads the series 4-2. 
</P>
