<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Walkout Could Stall Auto Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- While negotiators worked to avert a Teamsters  
strike against the 17 trucking companies that haul cars to dealers' 
showrooms, automakers made contingency plans to keep dealers 
supplied with their hot-selling products. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators face a deadline of 12:01 a.m. Tuesday, when the  
contract expires. Earlier this month, the truckers authorized their 
negotiating committee to call a strike if talks fail. 
</P>
<P>
	The showdown is the first test for James Hoffa since he became  
president of the Teamsters in March, assuming a post once held by 
his late father, Jimmy Hoffa. 
</P>
<P>
	Ian Hunter of the National Automobile Transporters Labor  
Division, one of the management organizations involved in the 
talks, said Friday that negotiations were intense. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is fair to say there are a number of major issues  
unresolved,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strike could throw a roadblock in front of the auto industry's  
record sales pace. So far this year, U.S. sales of new cars and 
light trucks are up 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters contract covers about 12,000 drivers, mechanics,  
yard and office workers nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	If a strike were called, industry officials expect the Teamsters  
initially would target just one of the major trucking companies 
that contract with automakers to move new cars to dealers from 
assembly plants, ports and rail yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Teamsters spokesman Chip Roth said Friday that the union could  
choose to strike some or all of the 17 trucking companies that are 
at the negotiating table. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters are seeking higher wages, improved pensions and  
health care, and a reduction in ``excessive work hours.'' They also 
are resisting proposals to pay lower salaries to entry-level 
drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Hunter said, automakers are pressing for lower prices  
from car haulers; labor costs have gone up 33 percent in the past 
four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our drivers are the highest paid in the trucking industry,''  
Hunter said. ``The average driver wage last year was $68,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers likely would use their own drivers and hire  
independents to help get some vehicles to dealers in the event of a 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're monitoring the situation closely,'' said Ford Motor Co.  
spokesman Ron Iori. ``We're hoping both the Teamsters and the 
haulers can reach a mutually agreeable situation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
