<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Accused of Selling 1,000 Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- A man sold as many as 1,000 semiautomatic  
pistols that were linked to robberies, homicides and other violent 
crimes, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury on Friday indicted Sean Twomey, 31, of  
Hayward. He allegedly used a falsified federal firearms license to 
obtain the guns from legitimate wholesalers and then distributed 
them with the help of convicted felons. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other men and a woman also were indicted.  
</P>
<P>
	Twomey allegedly obliterated the weapons' serial numbers to  
prevent their being traced back to him and sold them at a 
significant mark-up in the San Francisco Bay area, said Tracy Hite 
of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	The weapons, ranging from cheap Lorcin models to expensive  
Glocks, were used by criminals in at least three states, Hite said. 
About 40 pistols linked to criminal suspects have been recovered so 
far. 
</P>
<P>
	The ATF called the case ``the largest ongoing gun trafficking  
case in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twomey, jailed in Oakland, denied the allegations,  
court-appointed attorney Daniel Horowitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Horowitz said federal authorities were exaggerating to  
capitalize on national outrage over the shooting rampage last month 
at a Colorado high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Twomey's arraignment is set for June 7.  
</P>
<P>
	The maximum penalty for each conviction for using a false  
firearms license, or for being a felon in possession of a firearm, 
is 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
