<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Old Trieste Wins The Californian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Today was a good day for offspring of  
A.P. Indy at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Trieste, a 4-year-old son of A.P. Indy who was running in a  
race for the first time in almost nine months, led all the way in 
winning The Californian by seven lengths over Budroyale. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, A.P. Assay, a 5-year-old daughter of A.P.  
Indy who hadn't raced for nearly seven months, took the lead at the 
top of the stretch in winning the Desert Stormer Handicap by two 
lengths over Woodman's Dancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Chris McCarron and carrying 116 pounds, Old Trieste  
made it look easy in the $300,000 Grade II Californian, turning on 
the jets entering the final turn and pulling away for his decisive 
triumph. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very, very nice colt,'' McCarron said. ``It was a  
very impressive turn-of-foot he gave me after he ran as fast as he 
did down the backside. He gave me some goose bumps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Old Trieste hadn't run in a race since winning the Del Mar  
Breeders' Cup Handicap by five lengths last Sept. 6. The 
Kentucky-bred colt was sidelined due to a deep abscess in his left 
front foot. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Trieste bruised the same foot May 18, but trainer Mike Puype  
said it wasn't anything serious, and he was obviously correct. 
</P>
<P>
	``He ran out of his brains, what else can you say? I mean, it  
was awesome,'' Puype said. ``He is just a lot of horse, and if you 
knew even half the problems that he's been through -- he's just 
amazing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since finishing 10th in last year's Kentucky Derby almost 13  
months ago, Old Trieste has won all four of his races by a combined 
28 1/2 lengths. McCarron has been aboard all four times. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Trieste covered 1 1/8 miles in a swift 1:46 2-5 and, as the  
second-favorite in a field of seven, paid $6.80, $4.40 and $2.60. 
</P>
<P>
	The stakes record of 1:45 4-5 was set by Spectacular Bid in  
1980. Mud Route won the race last year in 1:48. 
</P>
<P>
	The win was the sixth in 11 lifetime starts for Old Trieste and  
was worth $180,000, raising his career earnings to $762,732. 
</P>
<P>
	Budroyale, ridden by Garrett Gomez and carrying 120 pounds,  
crossed the finish line 5 1/2 lengths in front of Puerto Madero and 
returned $4.40 and $2.40. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was phenomenal. I mean, my horse ran a phenomenal race,''  
Gomez said. ``He ran his eyeballs out. His legs just couldn't go as 
fast as that other horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Madero, the 11-10 favorite ridden by Kent Desormeaux and  
carrying high weight of 122 pounds, was two lengths ahead of 
Moore's Flat at the wire and paid $2.20 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Moore's Flat across the finish line in the 46th  
running of the race for 3-year-olds and up were Hal's Pal, Clover 
Hunter and Self Feeder. 
</P>
<P>
	Next for Old Trieste figures to be the $1 million Hollywood Gold  
Cup on June 27. Skip Away won the race last year, with Puerto 
Madero finishing second. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Eddie Delahoussaye and carrying 122 pounds, A.P. Assay  
covered six furlongs in 1:08 3-5 and, as the 3-5 favorite in the 
$106,000 race for fillies and mares, paid $3.20, $2.60 and $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was A.P. Assay's fifth in nine lifetime starts and  
was worth $63,600, raising the career earnings of the Kentucky-bred 
mare to $359,550. 
</P>
<P>
	A.P. Assay was running in her first race since finishing fifth  
in the Breeders' Cup Sprint last Nov. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodman's Dancer returned $4.40 and $2.10, and Corona Lake, who  
won the race last year, finished third this time and paid $2.10 to 
show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
