<HEADLINE> Airbus Confirms Sale of 57 Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Airbus has cut a deal to sell 57 airplanes, but  
will not disclose the buyer until later this year, the European 
consortium announced Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus, based in the southern French city of Toulouse, would not  
reveal the price of the deal, but the sale represents more than a 
third of the 152 aircraft it has sold this year. The buyer asked 
that the order, signed April 30, not immediately be disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal could be officially announced at the Paris Air Show,  
which runs from June 13-20. 
</P>
<P>
	The order is important for the company, said Michel Guerard,  
vice president for corporate communications. He noted that last 
year was a record year for the consortium with 556 aircraft sold, 
while 1999 is, so far, a ``moderate year'' for sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerard confirmed French press reports of the so-called  
``undisclosed'' sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The order includes 30 of Airbus' new A318 aircraft, which seats  
107 passengers and is aimed at short routes. It is to be assembled 
in Hamburg, Germany, and is expected to be operational by 2002. 
Also in the deal are 14 A319s, 10 A321s and 3 A320s. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus, the top competitor of Seattle-based Boeing Co., is owned  
by France's Aerospatiale, British Aerospace PLC, DaimlerChrysler 
Aerospace of Germany, and Construcciones Aeronauticas SA of Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
