<HEADLINE> Schnyder Dislikes Kournikova </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Anna Kournikova may be adored by the French fans,  
but she's not so well-liked by No. 11-seeded Patty Schnyder. 
</P>
<P>
	That's putting it mildly. The 20-year old Swiss player said  
after losing her match Saturday with the Russian star that she 
played badly because she so dislikes Kournikova. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a problem playing her,'' Schnyder said.  
</P>
<P>
	When asked if the problem was personal, she nodded in the  
affirmative. 
</P>
<P>
	This isn't the first time Schnyder's disike for Kournikova has  
affected her play. In April the two played each other in Florida at 
the Bausch &AMP; Lomb Championships and Schnyder seemed to tank the 
match. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate playing (Kournikova) and I don't play if I'm on the  
court with her,'' said Schnyder afterward. ``It's her ... and 
everything around her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Kournikova wouldn't speak about bad feelings  
between her and Schnyder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know her personally at all. There are a thousand  
players on the tour,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	COMPUTER GAME-SET-MATCH: While most tennis players want peace  
and quiet before a big match, Marat Safin spends his time playing 
video games. 
</P>
<P>
	An hour before he won his third-round match against Hicham  
Arazi, the Russian was playing a jet ski video game in the players 
lounge. 
</P>
<P>
	Safin proved a talented player of that game as well; he was  
second on the top-scoring list. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	FRIENDS AND FOES: Gustavo Kuerten came to the defense of Marcelo  
Rios Saturday. Rios gets terrible press in France due to his often 
surly temperament. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Kuerten, Rios is a nice, regular guy.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are very good friends,'' he said. ``We kind of have the  
same culture, so we talk a lot about what we like, soccer, music,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HELP NEEDED: Medical advice and good counseling is needed to  
help young female players determine if they're ready to be pros, 
Steffi Graf says. 
</P>
<P>
	When she started, Graf said, ``players used to be a lot  
skinnier, tinier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What is surprising to me is those girls, 12, 14-years old,  
they already have bodies that don't look like 13, 14-year-olds,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not allowing young players to play a full schedule of  
tournaments, as some have suggested, wouldn't help, she said. Some 
are just ready to play at an early age and should get proper 
advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, those players learn about their body very early on.  
I mean, that's the kind of education I think that's most 
important,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
