<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bench Is Key to Knicks-Pacers Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Forget the starters. It's the benches who  
may determine the Eastern Conference championship series between 
the Indiana Pacers and New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	For these are two of the NBA's deepest teams.  
</P>
<P>
	Latrell Sprewell, New York's leading scorer in the playoffs,  
comes off the bench and Marcus Camby has been a rebounding, scoring 
and shot-blocking force. Antonio Davis and Jalen Rose often play 
the key minutes for the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	Add Chris Dudley and Chris Childs for the Knicks and Travis Best  
and Derrick McKey and there's plenty of backup if the starters have 
an off night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks arrive in Market Square Arena having won five  
consecutive playoff games for the first time in franchise history, 
while Indiana's reserves have helped make the Pacers the only 
undefeated team in the playoffs with sweeps of Milwaukee and 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	If the series comes down to bench play, Indiana's Mark Jackson  
likes his team's chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't played them since they've been rolling,'' Jackson  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel we have the best bench in the game. That's no  
disrespect to anybody else's. When you have two guys finishing in 
the top for the sixth man of the year award, when you have the 
other guys coming in that can start on a lot of other teams, we 
feel very strong about our bench.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis and Rose finished in a tie for third place in voting for  
the sixth man award. The 6-foot-9, 230-pound Davis is a body-banger 
inside and Rose heads into Sunday's game as his team's 
second-leading scorer in the playoffs with a 13.4 mark. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our bench has been an important part of our team. We play 10  
guys all the time and divide the minutes according to how they're 
playing,'' said coach Larry Bird, no stranger to playoff success 
from his days starring for the Boston Celtics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know how we can win. We need a focused concentrated effort  
from our bench to keep going. These guys say they want a 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``Talk is fine, now our starters and reserves will have a chance  
to show how hard they want it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Mullin said Sprewell, Camby and Childs make the Knicks a  
more potent team than the one Indiana eliminated in last year's 
conference semifinals 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got a great card of bench players, great players. I  
don't know if you necessarily call them bench players because a lot 
of time they play as many or more minutes,'' said Mullin, a 
teammate of Sprewell's at Golden State. ``They've got a deep team 
and so do we. It's going to be important to not really worry about 
when you're on the floor, who you're matched up with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Effective play by Rose, Davis and McKey has cut into Mullin's  
playing time this season. That's of no concern to the veteran, who 
was the leading scorer against the Knicks this season with a 16.0 
average as Indiana won the season-series 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just go out there and play good minutes. If you play as  
hard as you can, and put it all together, that's what it's all 
about. It's not about how many minutes you play, how many shots you 
get, it's about winning the game,'' Mullin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose, meanwhile, wouldn't mind getting inside the heads of New  
York's players and some trash talk is as much a part of his game as 
his scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a fine line between competing and bagging down. A lot  
of this game is mental and a lot of this game is played from the 
heart,'' Rose said about the trash talk. ``If you can intimidate a 
guy, and if you can get into a guy's head for one play, or one 
game, or for a whole season to get a win. That's what it is all 
about.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
