<DOCNO> APW19990529.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 06:21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress To Reenter Transplant Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation circulating on Capitol Hill would  
remake organ transplant policy, giving the nation's transplant 
network virtually everything it has sought in a decade of disputes 
over who controls the distribution of scarce organs. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is the strongest challenge yet to the Clinton  
administration's effort to get organs to the sickest patients first 
-- even if they live farther away from the donor -- and to ensure 
that more data on the system is available to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	It comes as administration and transplant network officials  
resume closed-door talks in search of a compromise, nine months 
after the last round of talks broke off. 
</P>
<P>
	Years of tension between the Department of Health and Human  
Services and the United Network for Organ Sharing came to a head 
last year after HHS issued regulations overseeing the network's 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Most controversially, they require that organs be given to the  
sickest patients first. The current system relies heavily on 
geography, with patients located inside certain boundaries getting 
first chance at donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Congress stepped into the fight, suspending the  
controversial change until this fall. It also ordered an Institute 
of Medicine study of the system, which is expected in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the House Commerce Committee is poised to intervene again.  
The draft legislation would give the network, which runs the 
computers that match organs and recipients, virtually total control 
over allocation policy. 
</P>
<P>
	It would also allow the network to keep its budget secret and  
make it virtually impossible for HHS to contract with a different 
group to run the network. It also allows the network to keep secret 
data on the survival rates of patients at various hospitals and to 
disclose when a transplant center is under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., chairman of the Commerce health  
subcommittee, plans to introduce the bill next month and hopes it 
will be approved by the full panel this summer, said Todd Tuten, a 
Bilirakis aide who is helping to draft the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuten emphasized that the bill is still in draft form and could  
change before it is introduced, noting that it was based on the 
views of transplant surgeons and hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it stems from continued frustration over HHS's  
regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a concern about government bureaucrats making life  
and death allocation decisions,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	HHS says it is looking out for patients. The wait for a  
transplant varies significantly depending on location. In recent 
years, for instance, a typical liver patient waited less than two 
months in one part of the country but more than two years in 
another. 
</P>
<P>
	But the current system is supported by many transplant centers  
that rely on a local supply of organs to support their programs. If 
the organs followed the patients, many fear, they would flow to a 
few large centers, leaving smaller programs out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	Those transplant centers have bound together to fight the HHS  
rules, mounting a large lobbying campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, as the lobbying continues, HHS and network officials  
have returned to the table in an effort to reach a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-day meeting was held in early May, and the parties plan to  
meet again soon. Unlike talks last summer, these are more 
constructive as officials look for areas of potential agreement, 
said an HHS official who is part of the discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	A network spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
his side is cautiously optimistic that they can reach a resolution. 
But network officials had no comment on the proposed bill. 
</P>
<P>
	HHS is less optimistic about the pending legislation. The  
official, also speaking on condition of anonymity, called it ``an 
entire wish list'' for the network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
