<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	New Nigerian Leader Takes Office  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Olusegun Obasanjo became Nigeria's first  
civilian leader in 15 years today, expressing hope for a prosperous 
future for a nation tormented by years of dictatorship. Gen. 
Abdulsalami Abubakar, who during his 11 months in power has guided 
Nigeria peacefully through its transition to democracy, handed over 
power to Obasanjo. Africa's most populous nation, Nigeria has been 
governed by soldiers for all but 10 years since independence in 
1960. It has suffered dramatically under military rule and 
Obasanjo, who won February's presidential elections, faces a wealth 
of problems. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Jets Pound Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets struck hard today at Serb  
forces in the Kosovo province. NATO said its aircraft ``enjoyed 
considerable success'' on day 66 of its air campaign, aimed at 
forcing Yugoslavia to withdraw troops from Kosovo and allowing 
840,000 ethnic Albanian refugees to return under the protection of 
an international peacekeeping force. NATO said in a statement this 
morning at its headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, that alliance 
planes had flown 639 sorties, including 218 strike sorties, in the 
previous 24 hours. It said targets hit included at least 17 
artillery pieces and two tanks in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Indian Continues Kashmir Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Indian jets unleashed more attacks on Islamic  
guerrilla targets today in the disputed region of Kashmir, despite 
an offer from Pakistan to hold talks to diffuse tensions over the 
Himalayan territory claimed by both nuclear powers. India demanded 
the Pakistani government rein in its military, which New Delhi 
accuses of backing the guerrillas' incursion into the Indian-held 
part of Kashmir and their capture of mountain outposts. The Indian 
air force has been conducting strikes since Wednesday against 
positions held by the guerrillas, who India says include Pakistani 
soldiers disguised as militants. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Looks to U.N. for Help  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Pakistan has asked Secretary-General Kofi  
Annan for help in trying to reduce tensions with India. The 
neigbhboring nuclear rivals, embroiled in a conflict with India 
over Kashmir, have fought two of their three wars over the remote 
Himalayan region that lies between them. Pakistani Prime Minister 
Nawaz Sharif asked Annan to beef up the U.N. military observer 
mission in the disputed frontier, initiate a dialogue between India 
and Pakistan and dispatch a U.N. envoy to the region. 

</P>
<P>
	Shuttle Links With Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Discovery docked with the new  
international space station early today for six days of activities 
that include a spacewalk, repair work and supply transfers. The 
link marks another milestone for the new outpost, which was last 
visited by astronauts in December. With shuttle commander Kent 
Rominger at the controls, Discovery pulled up and latched on to the 
space station as it soared 240 miles above the border of Russia and 
Kazakstan. The crew will venture all the way inside the outpost for 
the first time Sunday, when they begin their maintenance work and 
start transferring two tons of supplies into the station. 

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Doctors Vote To Unionize  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hundreds of Los Angeles County doctors voted  
to unionize yesterday. They became part of a growing number of 
physicians across the nation who are unionizing, a trend stemming 
from the growing influence of health maintenance organizations and 
the belief that administrators have assumed too much influence over 
patient care, the doctors said. The 790 county doctors, many of 
whom care for the poor and uninsured, joined the Union of American 
Physicians and Dentists on a 341 to 182 vote, or 65 percent to 35 
percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Cathay Axes 24 Flights  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways canceled two dozen  
flights today following a sickout by pilots facing pay cuts and 
layoff threats. The Hong Kong carrier also has stopped taking 
bookings since late yesterday for flights flying in the next two 
weeks ``to ensure the situation is under control,'' an airline 
spokeswoman said. Passengers who have already booked their flights 
are not affected, she said. Cathay has an average of 116 flights 
daily. Cathay lost $69 million last year, the first loss in 35 
years. 

</P>
<P>
	Agassi Dazzles Roland Garros Crowd  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Andre Agassi made the shot of the year at the  
French Open, and in return, he might have received the ovation of 
the year. Trying to close off a rally, Agassi's opponent, Chris 
Woodruff, sent a near-perfect lob sailing over Agassi's head into 
the corner. Agassi sprinted back to the baseline, caught up with 
the lob, and, his back to the net, whacked the ball through his 
legs and hit a clean winner. Agassi defeated Wooduff, a fellow 
American, 6-4, 6-4, 6-3 to reach the round of 16 and a matchup 
against defending champion Carlos Moya. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
</TEXT>
