<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Revolution 4, MetroStars 3, SO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Giovanni Savarese scored two goals  
in his first game against his former MetroStars teammates and the 
New England Revolution beat New York-New Jersey in a shootout after 
playing a 3-3 tie tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	John Harkes scored the only goal in the shootout and backup  
goaltender Jeff Causey, who came on in the final two minutes of 
regulation time, didn't let the MetroStars beat him in giving the 
Revolution a 4-3 win. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan McKinley scored the other goal in regulation as New England  
snapped a two-game losing streak. Eduardo Hurtado, Arley Palacios 
and Brian Kelly scored for the MetroStars, who lost their second 
straight. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was the opener of a doubleheader at Giants Stadium that  
also featured an exhibition between Colombia and El Salvador. It 
attracted 43,192 fans, the largest crowd to see an MLS game this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The MetroStars and Revolution came into the game each having  
scored eight goals in their first nine games, but both found their 
scoring touches. 
</P>
<P>
	New England, which had not scored a goal in 340 minutes, scored  
twice in 13 minutes to take a 2-1 lead at halftime. 
</P>
<P>
	McKinley tied the game at 1-1 by running on a chip pass from  
Harkes in the box and heading it past Mike Ammann in the 21st 
minute. The play appeared to be offside. 
</P>
<P>
	Savarese, the MetroStars' all-time leading scorer with 41 goals  
before being traded to New England in the offseason, put the 
Revolution ahead in the 34th minute, converting in close off an 
assist by Joe-Max Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Palacios, a Medellin resident, delighted Colombian supporters in  
the crowd by tying the game on a 25-yard free kick in the 50th 
minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Savarese put the Revolution ahead again in the 54th with his  
second goal and fourth of the season. It was another play where he 
got behind the defense and no offside was called. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Kelly tied the game four minutes later, running onto a  
nice pass across the crease by Hurtado and knocking the ball into 
an open net. Hurtado had given the MetroStars a 1-0 lead in the 
sixth minute, scoring after New England starting goaltender Walter 
Zenga gave up a rebound on a Nansha Kalonji shot in the sixth 
minute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
