<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Keyes Cuts Into Conservative Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) -- Alan Keyes scowled at the 200 or so folks  
who had jumped to their feet in applause after his lengthy diatribe 
on America's evils. 
</P>
<P>
	``All that clapping doesn't mean anything unless you make a  
commitment to doing something,''' Keyes, who is making another bid 
for the GOP presidential nomination, said as aides passed out 
volunteer cards. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first political thing we've ever gone to,'' said  
Sharleen Hackley, gesturing at husband, Warner. ``The fact that he 
is here is remarkable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Filling a void, she said, is Keyes, a conservative  
African-American who argues abortion and a decline in religion are 
behind the nation's woes. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are things that are missing in our politicians today,''  
she said. ``He is very real.'' But a potential GOP nominee? 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't know that he has a real chance of winning,''  
Mrs. Hackley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Far below the radar of national politics, Keyes is readying for  
another run for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	He has a committee that allows him to travel to key early  
states. It is a shoestring operation compared with some rivals. 
Still, aides say they are happy with the way things are going. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Keyes showed a speaking style that could energize an  
audience, particularly conservatives, and captured 7 percent of the 
Republican vote in Iowa's leadoff precinct caucuses. Some 
strategists believe his presence prevented social conservatives 
from coalescing around a single candidate against Democrat Bill 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Since that election, Keyes has held more than 30 ``renewing  
America'' meetings in Iowa, where precinct caucuses launch the 
presidential nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	His appearances largely go unnoticed by reporters focusing on  
bigger-name contenders. Still, they draw impressive, say Iowa 
political leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's high on my list,'' said Daniel Nicholson, a city  
councilman from Dubuque. ``He has a message that none of the rest 
of them have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes twice ran for the U.S. Senate in Maryland, worked at the  
State Department official and was a radio talk show host with a 
gift for the rhetorical flourish that warms conservative hearts. 
</P>
<P>
	He spares neither Democrats nor Republicans, criticizing ``a  
political elite so utterly estranged from any connection to the 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Keyes has gotten little attention, he has the potential  
to split the votes of social conservatives who like his message 
even though his chances of winning seem remote. 
</P>
<P>
	``He draws very large crowds and he has very enthusiastic  
support,'' said Marlys Popma, political adviser to conservative 
activist Gary Bauer. ``I don't know if he's real.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Bob Haus, an aide to publisher Steve Forbes: ``He's not  
afraid to tackle some of those tough issues and people respond to 
that message.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some in the party say Keyes could help to shape the policy  
debate during the early stages of the campaign even if he is not a 
realistic contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``In smaller, early states he can be a force,'' said a former  
Iowa Republican chairman, Richard Schwarm. ``In bigger states later 
on he will fade.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 10:43:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Star Wars' Fans Swap Inside Trivia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Did baby talk really inspire the chattery  
beeps and squawks of R2-D2? 
</P>
<P>
	Was the Millennium Falcon starship modeled on a hamburger with  
an olive next to it? 
</P>
<P>
	Burt Reynolds considered as Han Solo?  
</P>
<P>
	True. True. And false.  
</P>
<P>
	With fans flocking to see ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom  
Menace,'' urban legends surrounding the films have become more 
plentiful than Yoda's grammatical mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of Web sites full of ``Star Wars'' trivia have popped up  
and newly enthusiastic fans are sharing insider tidbits like 
popcorn in freewheeling chat rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a quasi, national geek-pastime to studiously examine the  
existing films,'' said Paul Alvarado-Dykstra, a contributing editor 
on the movie-fan Web site aint-it-cool-news.com. ``It's hard to 
draw the line between what is really definitive or what is 
reinvented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spurious rumors have reached director George Lucas' headquarters  
at Skywalker Ranch in Novato, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``My favorite was the one about Kenneth Branagh playing Obi-Wan  
Kenobi, which was never true,'' said Lynn Hale, a Lucas 
spokeswoman. ``Everybody insisted he had the role, even after we 
said Ewan McGregor was cast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alternate casting is a favored item of ``Star Wars'' gossip,  
with fans speculating that everyone from Burt Reynolds to 
Christopher Walken were once signed to play rogue starship pilot 
Han Solo, the role that eventually made Harrison Ford famous. 
</P>
<P>
	``George says the Burt Reynolds claim is false,'' Ms. Hale said.  
Walken was in the running, eventually losing out to Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	But is it true Sissy Spacek was the first choice for Princess  
Leia? 
</P>
<P>
	As rumor has it, Carrie Fisher was playing the lead in the 1976  
Stephen King thriller ``Carrie'' but clashed with director Brian De 
Palma because she refused to do nude scenes. Spacek was reportedly 
unhappy with ``Star Wars,'' so the two actresses decided to switch 
roles. 
</P>
<P>
	``No way,'' said Ms. Hale, laughing.  
</P>
<P>
	Some of the seemingly ridiculous legends are true.  
</P>
<P>
	For instance, your mind isn't playing tricks on you if a  
gigantic potato or tennis shoe appears to float past the Millennium 
Falcon during its perilous flight through asteroids in ``The Empire 
Strikes Back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Employees at Industrial Light &AMP; Magic threw the items in as a  
joke. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas says he really was inspired to design the Millennium  
Falcon while staring at a hamburger with an olive next to it. 
</P>
<P>
	Even erroneous rumors associated with ``Star Wars'' sometimes  
have roots in reality. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Sound designer) Ben Burtt imitated the coos and babbling of  
babies and ... altered that sound to make the voice of R2-D2,'' 
said Ms. Hale. ``But he never used real babies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Burtt's fondness for using familiar, everyday noises  
rather than digitally created sound effects that led to the rumor 
that some ``Star Wars'' creatures say outrageous sentences in Earth 
languages. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Return of the Jedi,'' the cuddly Ewoks are rumored to speak  
a Filipino dialect and occasionally say things such as ``Det luktar 
flingor har,'' which is Swedish for ``It smells of corn flakes 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The speech patterns may be similar to those languages, but  
that's about all,'' Ms. Hale said. ``(Burtt) likes to use elements 
of real languages to form the ones used by these creatures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the latest hot topics among Star Wars aficionados?  
</P>
<P>
	E.T., Steven Spielberg's famous extraterrestrial, makes a  
background appearance in ``The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 03:01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Regains Control of Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Deborah Young remembers the last time the city  
was in control of its public housing. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-year resident of the Chicago's Robert Taylor Homes said  
roaches and rats infested her South Side building and officials and 
residents were mired in apathy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was utter chaos. There were no services; the buildings were  
filthy and dangerous. It was as if everything had come to a stop,'' 
Young said. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government stepped in and seized the Chicago Housing  
Authority in 1995. After that, Young said, ``We went from being 
hopeless and traumatized communities to communities with hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, nearly four years after the Department of Housing and Urban  
Development's takeover, the federal agency is returning the 
troubled CHA to local control. 
</P>
<P>
	Young wonders if Mayor Richard Daley's administration is up to  
the task of running the approximately 62,000 unit system. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know their plans for us. It's a matter of whether  
they can keep moving in the right direction,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a huge task,'' Daley said. ``It won't happen  
overnight. It will take years to complete. We all must be willing 
to experiment and learn as we go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago officials and HUD signed an agreement restoring the  
city's control of the CHA on Thursday, nearly nine months after the 
agency was removed from a federal list of troubled housing 
authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	HUD stepped in after a series of scandals, including allegations  
that a former board chairman embezzled millions of dollars from the 
housing authority's pension funds. At the time, HUD Secretary Henry 
Cisneros said the CHA was ``without question, the worst public 
housing in America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Current HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo called the return to local  
control a ``vote of confidence in the good work'' of Daley and the 
CHA to improve living conditions in public housing. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Shuldiner, who was sent by HUD to run the housing  
authority, said rampant mismanagement has been eliminated while 
economic opportunities have increased for residents through job 
training programs and small-business initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	HUD also has awarded more than $100 million in grants for  
rehabilitation. Some buildings have been torn down; others have 
been modernized. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been able to give the CHA back its credibility, ''  
Shuldiner said. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everyone considers the CHA's development under HUD an  
unequivocal success. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberta Feldman, an urban planner with the University of  
Illinois at Chicago, acknowledges more efficient management of the 
CHA has allowed more funds to make their way to the housing 
complexes. 
</P>
<P>
	But many of the challenges -- including keeping crumbling and  
aging complexes livable -- remain, she said. And new problems have 
cropped up because of a shift in government policy on public 
housing that has called for the demolition of some 10,000 public 
housing units in Chicago in favor of mixed income housing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many residents are feeling anxious about whether they are  
going to have a home,'' Feldman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley's appointment of Phillip Jackson as the CHA's new  
executive director is seen by some as a cause for optimism. 
Jackson, a former Chicago public housing resident, has been a top 
administrator for the city's school system. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Jackson) is going to relate to residents and challenge the  
residents. He is going to be tough-minded and tender-hearted,'' 
said Rep. Danny Davis, a Democrat whose district contains about 68 
percent of Chicago's public housing complexes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990529.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 13:21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> What Reggie Miller Do This Time?  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Nothing quite captures the spirit of the  
Knicks-Pacers rivalry than the memory of one of Reggie Miller's 
greatest moments. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison Square Garden, May 7, 1995: Eight points in the final  
8.9 seconds, six of them coming on 3-pointers right in front of 
Spike Lee's courtside seat. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the quintessential Miller moment, a Knick-killing  
sequence that remains so vivid in the minds of the Indiana Pacers 
that they were talking Saturday like it happened just yesterday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Watching Spike Lee, watching his face during that period after  
all the talking, it was good to watch his face,'' Mark Jackson 
recalled. ``It was almost like he was watching the final edit of 
one of his movies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Rik Smits: ``If I had to pick one game, it would be the  
eight points in the last seconds of that game. I scored 34, but he 
came up big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody knew it at the time, but Miller's 8.9-second outburst  
would usher in a four-year period in which the Knicks would not be 
able to get out of the second round of the playoffs. Now New York 
is back in the Eastern Conference finals for the first time since 
1994, playing an Indiana team that has been this far in the 
playoffs three times, only to lose a Game 7 each time. 
</P>
<P>
	Game 1 in the best-of-7 series tips off at 5:30 p.m. EDT Sunday  
at Market Square Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller himself wasn't talking about anything Saturday in keeping  
with his recent persona of being Mr. Anti-Inflammatory. 
</P>
<P>
	He gave no insight into his famous 8.9 seconds in 1995, his  
25-point fourth-quarter against the Knicks in Game 5 of the 1994 
conference finals, or his 3-pointer in New York during Game 4 of 
last season's second-round playoff series -- another shot from right 
in front of Lee's seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't particularly like him too much in New York, and he  
probably feels the same way about this organization,'' the Knicks' 
Latrell Sprewell said. ``But he obviously respects us, and this 
city respects him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This will be the fifth time the teams have met in the playoffs  
in the past seven seasons. The Knicks beat Indiana 3-1 in the first 
round in 1993 and 4-3 in the conference finals in 1994. The Pacers 
defeated the Knicks 4-3 in the second round in 1995 and 4-1 in the 
second round in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indiana still has a lot of the same players, but we've changed  
personnel so much,'' said New York coach Jeff Van Gundy, who has 
been through all the Pacers-Knicks series either as an assistant 
coach or a head coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy will bring a different version of the Knicks into  
Indianapolis, a team more inclined to run and gun than the old New 
York teams that would pound the ball into the low post and watch 
Patrick Ewing operate. 
</P>
<P>
	With a younger, more athletic second unit that includes Sprewell  
and Marcus Camby, the Knicks will try to force the tempo against a 
Pacers team that remains perfectly happy in a slow-down, half-court 
offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers won the season series 2-1, winning decisively in the  
two games at Market Square Arena and losing by one point in the one 
matchup at Madison Square Garden. But both those games have little 
meaning now. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks have turned things around over the past six weeks,  
finishing the regular season strong, beating Miami in the first 
round of the playoffs and then sweeping the Atlanta hawks in the 
second round. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers, meanwhile, have been nearly flawless, sweeping both  
Milwaukee and Philadelphia in the first two rounds of the playoffs 
as part of an 11-game winning streak they'll bring into Sunday's 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams have had plenty of rest heading into this series.  
Indiana hasn't played since last Sunday, while New York has been 
off since Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two or three days of rest would have been fine,'' Smits said.  
``This is getting old. It's been a long, long week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So long, in fact, that the Pacers have had time to dissect the  
journalistic merits of a quote by Jackson -- he called the Pacers 
``the champs'' -- that was turned into a back-page headline in one 
of the New York tabloids. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson contends the comment was an innocuous one.  
</P>
<P>
	``Friends have faxed me stuff, and family members have called  
and told me what was going on,'' he said. ``It gets old. It's sad, 
really. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't care,'' said Jackson who grew up in New York  
and started his career with the Knicks. ``What are they going to 
do, boo me? They did that when I played there, so it doesn't make 
any difference.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
