<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 00:01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> War Heroes Honored With Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photos NA101-102    	
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Rick Pittman was overwhelmed as he gazed up  
at the names etched in the glass of the new Medal of Honor 
Memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's awesome,'' the 53-year-old Vietnam veteran said at  
Friday's dedication of the first monument to the 3,410 recipients 
of America's highest distinction for military valor. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittman and 92 other Medal of Honor recipients were the first to  
see and touch the monument to their heroics, built on the banks of 
a canal that runs through downtown Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wear these medals, not for ourselves, but for those who  
served with us and whose work went unseen,'' said Paul Bucha, who 
earned the medal while serving in the Army in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of the ceremony, a giant curtain of American flags  
parted so hundreds of onlookers could see the memorial; the 
audience exploded into a standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	The monument's 27 curved glass panels rise above the canal,  
representing 15 military conflicts dating to the Civil War. At 
dusk, the monument will play recorded stories -- narrated by some of 
the servicemen. 
</P>
<P>
	Loved ones scoured the panels Friday for names etched in glass  
alongside their branch of service and the site of their heroic act. 
Cries of ``Here, you are!'' echoed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tremendous,'' said medal-bearer Lewis Millett, a 78-year-old  
Korean War veteran from Idyllwild, Calif. ``I can't believe it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IPALCO Enterprises Inc., a holding company for the electrical  
utility that serves Indianapolis, spent $2.5 million to build the 
memorial. It also paid to bring to Indianapolis as many surviving 
Medal of Honor recipients as possible for the dedication over 
Memorial Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just ordinary men, and we were very fortunate to do  
deeds that were seen,'' said Stephen Gregg, 84, of Bayonne, N.J., 
who dodged gunfire and grenades to give cover to a medic who 
rescued seven wounded soldiers in France during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The medal-bearers were to serve as grand marshals of the  
Indianapolis 500 Festival Parade today, and will ride around 
Indianapolis Motor Speedway before Sunday's big race. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
